{"title_page": "Arthur Griffith", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|Irish politician and writer, founder of Sinn Fein}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Arthur Griffith\n| nationality   = Irish\n| image         = Arthur Griffith.jpg\n| office        = [[President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]]\n| term_start    = 10 January 1922\n| term_end      = 12 August 1922\n| predecessor   = [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] <small>(As President of the Irish Republic)</small>\n| successor     = [[W. T. Cosgrave]]\n| office2       = Minister for Foreign Affairs\n| term_start2   = 26 August 1921\n| term_end2     = 9 January 1922\n| predecessor2  = [[George Noble Plunkett|Count Plunkett]]\n| successor2    = [[George Gavan Duffy]]\n| office3       = Minister for Home Affairs\n| term_start3   = 2 April 1919\n| term_end3     = 22 August 1921\n| predecessor3  = [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]\n| successor3    = [[Austin Stack]]\n| office4       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start4   = 1921\n| term_end4     = 1922\n| constituency4 = [[Cavan (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cavan]]\n| term_start5   = 1921\n| term_end5     = 1922\n| constituency5 = [[Fermanagh and Tyrone (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh and Tyrone]]\n| term_start6   = 1918\n| term_end6     = 1921\n| constituency6 = [[East Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|East Cavan]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1871|3|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1922|8|12|1871|3|31|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Dublin, Ireland\n| party         = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n| spouse        = Maud Sheehan\n| children      = 2\n|}}\n'''Arthur Joseph Griffith''' ({{lang-ga|Art Seosamh \u00d3 Gr\u00edobhtha}}; 31 March 1871 \u2013 12 August 1922) was an Irish writer, newspaper editor and politician who founded the political party [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. He led the Irish delegation at the negotiations that produced the 1921 [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]], and served as [[President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] from January 1922 until his death in August 1922.\n\nAfter a short spell in [[South Africa]], Griffith founded and edited the [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalist]] newspaper ''[[United Irishman|The United Irishman]]'' in 1899. In 1904, he wrote ''[[The Resurrection of Hungary|The Resurrection of Hungary: A Parallel for Ireland]]'', which advocated the withdrawal of Irish members from the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] and the setting up of the institutions of government at home, a policy that became known as {{lang|ga|Sinn F\u00e9in}} (ourselves). On 28 November 1905, he presented \"The Sinn F\u00e9in Policy\" at the first annual convention of his organisation, the National Council; the occasion is marked as the founding date of the Sinn F\u00e9in party. Griffith took over as president of Sinn F\u00e9in in 1911, but at that time the organisation was still small.\n\nGriffith was arrested following the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916, despite not having taken any part in it. On his release, he worked to build up Sinn F\u00e9in, which won a string of by-election victories. At the party's {{lang|ga|[[Ardfheis]]}} (annual convention) in October 1917, Sinn F\u00e9in became an unambiguously [[Irish republicanism|republican]] party, and Griffith resigned the presidency in favour of the 1916 leader [[\u00c9amon de Valera]], becoming vice-president instead. Griffith was elected as a member of parliament (MP) for [[East Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|East Cavan]] in a [[by-election]] in June 1918, and re-elected in the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 general election]], when Sinn F\u00e9in won a huge electoral victory over the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] and, refusing to take their seats at Westminster, set up their own constituent assembly, [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (Irish Republic)|D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]].<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Arthur-Griffith.D.1919-01-21/|title=Arthur Griffith|work=Oireachtas Members Database|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the D\u00e1il, Griffith served as Minister for Home Affairs from 1919 to 1921, and Minister for Foreign Affairs from 1921 to 1922. In September 1921, he was appointed chairman of the Irish delegation to negotiate a treaty with the British government. After months of negotiations, he and the other four delegates signed the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]], which created the [[Irish Free State]], but not as a republic. This led to a split in the D\u00e1il. After the Treaty was narrowly approved by the D\u00e1il, de Valera resigned as president and Griffith was elected in his place. The split led to the [[Irish Civil War]]. Griffith died suddenly in August 1922, two months after the outbreak of that war.\n\n==Family and early life==\nArthur Joseph Griffith was born at 61 Upper Dominick Street, [[Dublin]] on 31 March 1871,<ref name=birth>{{cite web|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/images/birth_returns/births_1871/03298/2208617.pdf|title=31st March 1871 - Birth of Arthur Griffith|work=Civil Records on Irish Genealogy Site|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> of distant Welsh lineage. His great-great-grandfather, William Griffith of Drws-y-coed Uchaf, [[Rhyd-ddu]], [[Caernarvonshire]] (1719-1782), was a farmer and supporter of the [[Moravian Church]] cause. His great grandfather, Griffith Griffith (b.1789), emigrated first to America and then to Ireland, where some of his sisters had settled in Dublin among the Moravian community there.<ref>R.T. Jenkins, ''The Moravian Brethren in North Wales'', (Hon. Soc. of Cymmrodorion, London, 1938, pp.82-6, 151-4; broadcast gan Karen Owen, Radio Cymru, ''Rhaglen Dei Tomos'', 24.02.2019</ref> A Roman Catholic,<ref name=\"Maye, Brian 1997, p368\">Maye, Brian: ''Arthur Griffith'', Dublin, Griffith College Publications, 1997, p. 368<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref> he was educated by the Irish [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]]. He worked for a time as a printer before joining the [[Gaelic League]], which was aimed at promoting the restoration of the [[Irish language]].\n\nHis father had been a printer on ''[[The Nation (Irish newspaper)|The Nation]]'' newspaper \u2014 Griffith was one of several employees locked out in the early 1890s due to a dispute with a new owner of the paper. The young Griffith was a member of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]] (IRB). He visited [[South Africa]] from 1897 to 1898, after the defeat and death of [[Charles Stewart Parnell]], whose more moderate views he had initially supported, and while he was recovering from [[tuberculosis]]. There he supported the [[Boers]] against British expansionism and was a strong admirer of [[Paul Kruger]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\nIn 1899, on returning to [[Dublin]], he co-founded the weekly ''[[United Irishman]]'' newspaper with his associate [[William Rooney]], who died in 1901. On 24 November 1910, Griffith married his fianc\u00e9e, Maud Sheehan, after a six-year engagement; they had a son and a daughter.<ref>Arthur Griffith by Owen Magee, 2015</ref>\n\nGriffith's fierce criticism of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]]'s alliance with the British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] was heavily influenced by the anti-Liberal rhetoric of [[Young Ireland]]er [[John Mitchel]]. Griffith also expressed a number of highly-controversial opinions. He defended [[antisemitic]] rioters in [[Limerick]], and denounced socialists and [[pacifism|pacifists]] as conscious tools of the [[British Empire]]. Griffith also supported movements seeking national independence from the British Empire in [[Egypt]] and [[India]], and wrote a highly-critical description of the British government action at [[Northern Ndebele people|Matabele]]. Despite his opposition to communism and socialism, he sometimes worked with [[James Connolly]], who also supported Irish nationalism.<ref>[http://www.historyireland.com/20th-century-contemporary-history/arthur-griffith-brian-maye-griffith-college-publications-25-isbn-0-9531611-0-2/ Review of Brian Maye's ''Arthur Griffith'' by Patrick Maume], ''History Ireland'', 6:1 (Spring 1998)</ref>\n\nIn September 1900, he established an organisation called ''[[Cumann na nGaedheal (1900)|Cumann na nGaedheal]]'' (\"Society of Gaels\"), to unite advanced nationalist and [[separatist]] groups and clubs. In 1903, he set up the National Council, to campaign against the visit to Ireland of [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|King Edward VII]] and his consort [[Alexandra of Denmark]].<ref>Irish Leaving cert history textbook; Movements for Political and Social Reform 1870\u20131914.</ref> In 1907, that organisation merged with the Sinn F\u00e9in League, which itself had been formed from an amalgamation of Cumann na nGaedheal and the Dungannon Clubs, to form what would become Sinn F\u00e9in.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boyce|first1=D. George|last2=O'Day|first2=Alan|authorlink1=D. G. Boyce|title=Ireland in Transition, 1867-1921|date=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1134320000|page=155|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=68JG1dTxUcgC&pg=PA155|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, after the ''United Irishman'' journal collapsed because of a libel suit, Griffith re-founded it under the title ''[[Sinn F\u00e9in (newspaper)|Sinn F\u00e9in]]''. It briefly became a daily in 1909 and survived until its suppression by the British government in 1914, after which Griffith became editor of the new nationalist journal, ''Nationality''.\n\n==Foundation of Sinn F\u00e9in==\nMost historians opt for 28 November 1905 as a founding date because it was on this date that Griffith first presented his 'Sinn F\u00e9in Policy'. In his writings, Griffith declared that the [[Act of Union 1800|Act of Union of Great Britain and Ireland in 1800]] was illegal and that, consequently, the Anglo-Irish dual monarchy that existed under [[Grattan's Parliament]] and the so-called ''[[Constitution of 1782]]'' were still in effect. Its first president was [[Edward Martyn]].\n\nThe fundamental principles of abstentionism on which Sinn F\u00e9in was founded were outlined in an article published in 1904, by Griffith called ''[[The Resurrection of Hungary]]'', in which, noting how in 1867 Hungary went from being ''part'' of the [[Austrian Empire]] to a separate co-equal kingdom in [[Austria-Hungary]]. Though not a [[monarchism|monarchist]] himself, Griffith advocated such an approach for the [[Anglo-Irish]] relationship, namely that Ireland should become a separate kingdom alongside Great Britain, the two forming a [[dual monarchy]] with a shared monarch but separate governments, as it was thought this solution would be more palatable to the British.<ref name=\"ResurrectionOfIreland\" /> This was similar to the policy of [[Henry Grattan]] a century earlier. However, this idea was never really embraced by later separatist leaders, especially [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]], and never came to anything, although [[Kevin O'Higgins]] toyed with the idea as a means of ending [[Partition of Ireland|partition]], shortly before his assassination in 1927.\n\nGriffith sought to combine elements of [[Charles Stewart Parnell|Parnellism]] with the traditional separatist approach; he saw himself not as a leader but as providing a strategy which a new leader might follow. Central to his strategy was parliamentary [[abstentionism|abstention]]: the belief that Irish [[Member of Parliament|MPs]] should refuse to attend the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] at [[Westminster]], but should instead establish a separate Irish parliament (with an administrative system based on local government) in Dublin.\n\nGriffith was a staunch [[Economic nationalism|economic nationalist]], he argued that nationalism was central to the fostering of economic growth. He often cited the works of German economist [[Friedrich List]].<ref name=\"ResurrectionOfIreland\">{{Cite book|title=The Resurrection of Ireland: The Sinn F\u00e9in Party 1916-1923|last=Laffan|first=Michael|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=223}}</ref>\n\nIn 1907, Sinn F\u00e9in unsuccessfully contested a by-election in [[North Leitrim (UK Parliament constituency)|North Leitrim]], where the sitting MP, one [[Charles Dolan (politician)|Charles Dolan]] of [[Manorhamilton]], [[County Leitrim]], had defected to Sinn F\u00e9in. At this time Sinn F\u00e9in was being infiltrated by the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]], who saw it as a vehicle for their aims; it had several local councillors (mostly in Dublin, including [[W. T. Cosgrave]]) and contained a dissident wing grouped from 1910 around the monthly periodical called ''Irish Freedom''. The IRB members argued that the aim of dual monarchism should be replaced by republicanism and that Griffith was excessively inclined to compromise with conservative elements (notably in his pro-employer position during the 1913\u20131914 [[Dublin Lockout]], when he saw the syndicalism of [[James Larkin]] as aimed at crippling Irish industry for Great Britain's benefit).\n\nIn 1911, he helped to found the [[Proportional Representation Society of Ireland]], believing that [[proportional representation]] would help to prevent animosity between unionists and nationalists in an independent Ireland.<ref>John Coakley and Michael Gallagher, ''Politics in the Republic of Ireland'' (Taylor & Francis, 2010), 113.</ref>\n\n==1916 Rising==\nIn 1916, rebels seized and took over a number of key locations in Dublin, in what became known as the [[Easter Rising]]. After its defeat, it was widely described both by British politicians and the Irish and British media as the \"Sinn F\u00e9in rebellion\", even though Sinn F\u00e9in had very limited involvement. When in 1917, surviving leaders of the rebellion were released from gaol (or escaped) they joined Sinn F\u00e9in ''en masse'', using it as a vehicle for the advancement of the republic. The result was a bitter clash between those original members who backed Griffith's concept of an Anglo-Irish dual monarchy and the new members, under [[\u00c9amon de Valera]], who wanted to achieve a republic. Matters almost led to a split at the party's Ard Fheis (conference) in October 1917.\n\nIn a compromise, it was decided to seek to establish a republic initially, then allow the people to decide whether they wanted a republic or a monarchy, subject to the condition that no member of Britain's royal house could sit on any prospective Irish throne.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Packenham|first1=Frank|title=\u00c9amon de Valera|date=1974|publisher=Arrow Books|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r7MMAQAAMAAJ&q=%22no+contemplation+in+it%22|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> At that Ard Fheis, Griffith resigned the presidency of Sinn F\u00e9in in favour of de Valera; he and [[Michael O'Flanagan|Fr. Michael O'Flanagan]] were elected Vice-Presidents. The leaders of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] (IPP) sought a rapprochement with Griffith over the British threat of [[conscription]], which both parties condemned, but Griffith refused unless the IPP embraced his more radical and subversive ideals, a suggestion which [[John Dillon]], a leader of the IPP rubbished as unrealistic, although it would ultimately mean the defeat and dissolution of the IPP after the election in December 1918.\n\n==War of Independence==\n[[File:Arthur Griffith 071022.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Griffith seen in July 1922, a month before his death]]\nIn May 1918, along with \u00c9amon de Valera and 72 other Sinn F\u00e9iners, Griffith was arrested on the pretext of involvement in the fictitious [[German Plot (Ireland)|German Plot]]. Griffith spent ten months interned in Gloucester jail, being released on 6 March 1919. Fr. O'Flanagan was left as Acting-President of Sinn F\u00e9in.<ref name=Carroll>{{Cite book|title=They Have Fooled You Again|last=Carroll|first=Denis|publisher=The Columba Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-78218-300-6|location=|pages=}}{{Page number missing|date=February 2019}}</ref>  Griffith was put forward as a Sinn F\u00e9in candidate for the [[1918 East Cavan by-election|East Cavan by-election]] on 20 June 1918.<ref>Maume, Patrick: ''The long Gestation, Irish Nationalist Life 1891\u20131918'' p. 207 (note 322), Gill & Macmillan (1999); {{ISBN|0-7171-2744-3}}</ref> Under the slogan \"Put him in to get him out,\" and was elected. and held the seat when Sinn F\u00e9in subsequently routed the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] at the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 general election]] with a commitment of [[abstentionism]] from the [[British House of Commons]].<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=1082|title=Arthur Griffith|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=1 June 2009}}</ref> Griffith was returned for  returned for both East Cavan and [[North West Tyrone (UK Parliament constituency)|Tyrone North West]].\n\nSinn F\u00e9in's MPs set up an Irish parliament, [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (1919-1922)|D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] and [[Irish Declaration of Independence|declared independence]] for the [[Irish Republic]]; the [[Irish War of Independence]] followed almost immediately. The dominant leaders in the D\u00e1il included \u00c9amon de Valera, [[President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] (1919\u201321), President of the Republic (1921\u20131922), and [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]], [[Minister for Finance (Ireland)|Minister for Finance]], head of the IRB and the [[Irish Republican Army]]'s Director of Intelligence.\n\nDuring de Valera's absence in the [[United States]] (1919\u201321) Griffith served as Acting President and gave regular press interviews. He was arrested at his house at 3am, on 26 November 1920, and later jailed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1920/nov/26/mr-arthur-griffith-arrest |title=MR. ARTHUR GRIFFITH (ARREST). (Hansard, 26 November 1920) |website=Hansard.millbanksystems.com |date=1920-11-26 |accessdate=2017-05-28}}</ref> Fr. O'Flanagan again taking over as acting leader until de Valera returned from America on 23 December.<ref name=Carroll/> Griffith was to spend the next seven months in Dublin's [[Mountjoy Prison]]. He was released on 30 June 1921 as peace moves got under way.\n\nIn Ireland, a [[1921 Irish elections|general election]] was held on 24 May 1921 and Griffith, while still in prison, headed the poll in the contested constituency of [[Fermanagh and Tyrone (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh and Tyrone]], and was returned unopposed for [[Cavan (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cavan]]. On 26 August 1921, Griffith was appointed [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] in the new Irish cabinet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1921-08-26/4/|title=THE NEW MINISTRY \u2013 D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2nd D\u00e1il) \u2013 Friday, 26 August 1921|access-date=19 March 2020|website=Houses of the Oireachtas|date=26 August 1921}}</ref>\n\n==Treaty negotiations and death==\n[[File:Arthur Griffith Grave.jpg|thumb|right|Griffith's grave in [[Glasnevin Cemetery]], Dublin]]\nIn September 1921, de Valera, President of the Republic, asked Griffith to head the delegation of Irish plenipotentiaries to negotiate with the British government. The delegates set up Headquarters in [[Hans Place]], London. After nearly two months of negotiations, on 5 December, the delegates decided in private conversation in their headquarters to sign the Treaty and recommened it the to D\u00e1il; negotiations closed at 2.20am on 6 December 1921. Griffith was the member of the treaty delegation most supportive of its eventual outcome, a compromise based on [[dominion]] status, rather than a republic. The Treaty [[Anglo-Irish Treaty D\u00e1il vote|was ratified by the D\u00e1il]] by 64 votes to 57 on 7 January 1922. On 9 January, de Valera stood down as President and sought re-election by the D\u00e1il, which he lost by a vote of 58 to 60.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1922-01-09/2/|title=RESIGNATION OF PRESIDENT \u2013 D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2nd D\u00e1il) \u2013 Monday, 9 January 1922|access-date=31 August 2019|website=Houses of the Oireachtas|date=9 January 1922}}</ref> Griffith then succeeded de Valera as President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1922-01-10/2/|title=ELECTION OF PRESIDENT \u2013 D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2nd D\u00e1il) \u2013 Tuesday, 10 January 1922|access-date=31 August 2019|website=Houses of the Oireachtas|date=10 January 1922}}</ref> A second ratification of the Treaty by the [[House of Commons of Southern Ireland]] followed shortly afterwards. Griffith was, however, to a great extent merely a figurehead as President of the [[Second D\u00e1il]] and his relations with Michael Collins, head of the new [[Provisional Government]], were somewhat tense.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nSuffering from overwork and strain after the long and difficult negotiations with the [[British government]], Griffith attended forty-one of the forty-two\nprovisional government meetings held between 23 June and 30 July, and the work involved in establishing the Free State government, he entered St. Vincent's Nursing Home, [[Leeson Street]], Dublin, during the first week of August 1922, following an acute attack of tonsillitis.<ref>{{cite book|last=Glandon|first=Virginia E.|title = Arthur Griffith and the Advanced-nationalist Press, Ireland, 1900\u20131922|publisher=P. Lang|year=1985|page=230|isbn=0-8204-0041-6}}</ref> He was confined to a room in St Vincent's by his doctors, who had observed signs of what they thought might be a [[subarachnoid hemorrhage]], but it was difficult to keep him quiet,<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Connor|first=Ulick|authorlink=|title=Michael Collins and the Troubles|publisher=W.W. Norton|year=1996|isbn=0-393-31645-9|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/michaelcollinst00ocon}}</ref> and he resumed his daily work in the government building. He had been about to leave for his office shortly before 10 am on 12 August 1922, when he paused to retie his shoelace and fell down unconscious. He regained consciousness, but collapsed again with blood coming from his mouth. Three doctors rendered assistance, but to no avail. Fr John Lee of the [[Marist Fathers]] administered [[extreme unction]], and Griffith expired as the priest recited the concluding prayer. The cause of death, [[cerebral haemorrhage]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/details-civil/c764409590352|title=General Registrar's Office|last=|first=|date=|website=IrishGenealogy.ie|publisher=|access-date=12 August 2017}}</ref> was also reported as being due to heart failure.<ref name=nyt19220813>{{Cite news|title=Arthur Griffith Dies Suddenly|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=13 August 1922|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/08/13/107066789.pdf}}</ref> He died at the age of 51, ten days before [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]' assassination in [[County Cork]]. He was buried in [[Glasnevin Cemetery]] four days later.\n\n==Posthumous commemoration==\nThe historian [[Diarmaid Ferriter]] considers that, though he had founded Sinn F\u00e9in, Griffith was 'quickly airbrushed' from Irish history. His widow had to beg his former colleagues for a pension, saying that he 'had made them all'. She considered that his grave plot was too modest and threatened to exhume his body. Only in 1968 was a plaque fixed on his former home.<ref>Ferriter, D. ''The Transformation of Ireland 1900\u20132000'' (Profile 2004) p. 260; {{ISBN|1-86197-307-1}}</ref>\n\n[[Griffith Barracks]] which is now [[Griffith College Dublin]] on [[South Circular Road, Dublin]], [[R102 road (Ireland)|Griffith Avenue]] in North Dublin, Griffith Park in [[Drumcondra, Dublin|Drumcondra]] and Arthur Griffith Park in [[Lucan, County Dublin]] are named after him. An obelisk erected in 1950 in the grounds of [[Leinster House]] commemorates Griffith, as well as [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]] and [[Kevin O'Higgins]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The OPW \u2013 a history of service|year=2006|publisher=The Office of Public Works|page=5|url=http://irishartsreview.com/irisartsrevi2002/pdf/2006/25503509.pdf.bannered.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120917014345/http://irishartsreview.com/irisartsrevi2002/pdf/2006/25503509.pdf.bannered.pdf|archivedate=17 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Claims of antisemitism==\nIn 1997, [[Simon Sebag Montefiore]] wrote an article in ''[[The Spectator]]'' which, he claimed, \"exposes the role of Sinn Fein's founder in an Irish persecution of Jews.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Montefiore |first1=Simon Sebag |title=Arthur Griffith, anti-Semite |url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/11th-october-1997/28/arthur-griffith-anti-semite |accessdate=7 February 2019 |work=[[The Spectator]] |date=11 October 1997 |pages=28\u201330 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> No such claim has been made in any biography of Griffith or history of early Sinn F\u00e9in before then, or immediately afterwards.<ref>{{cite book |last1=\u00d3 L\u00faing |first1=Se\u00e1n |title=Art \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa |date=1953 |publisher=S\u00e1irs\u00e9al agus Dill}}; {{cite book |last1=Colum |first1=Padraic |title=Arthur Griffith |url=https://archive.org/details/arthurgriffith0000colu |url-access=registration |date=1959 |publisher=Browne and Nolan}}; {{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Richard P. |title=Arthur Griffith and Non-Violent Sinn Fein |date=1974 |publisher=Anvil Books}}; {{cite book |last1=Laffan |first1=Michael |title=The Resurrection of Ireland: The Sinn F\u00e9in Party 1916-1923 |date=1999 |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>\n\nAs editor of the ''[[United Irishman]]'', Griffith took an [[Anti-Dreyfusard]] line, publishing articles signed by 'The Home Secretary' ([[Frank Hugh O'Donnell]]) that were anti-Semitic in tone, including one in 1899 that stated: \"I have in former years often declared that the Three Evil Influences of the century were the Pirate, the Freemason, and the Jew.\"<ref name=keogh>{{cite book|last=Keogh|first=Dermot|title=Jews in Twentieth-century Ireland: Refugees, Anti-semitism and the Holocaust|publisher=Cork University Press|year=1998|page=22|isbn=1-85918-150-3}}</ref> In 1904, the paper voiced support for the [[Limerick Boycott]], a boycott of Jewish businesses in Limerick organised by a local priest, declaring that \"the Jew in Limerick has not been boycotted because he is a Jew, but because he is a usurer.\" Griffith was apparently unaware that the Jews of Limerick had little or no involvement in money-lending or similar practices.<ref name=\"Maye, Brian 1997, p368\"/><ref name=McGee409>{{cite book |last1=McGee |first1=Owen |title=Arthur Griffith |date=2015 |publisher=Merrion Press |isbn=978-1-78537-009-0 |page=409 (fn 62)}}</ref> The ''United Irishman'' also published articles by [[Oliver St. John Gogarty]] that contained antisemitic sentiments. Such sentiments, however, were common in the Ireland of the time.<ref name=Kenny1>{{cite journal |last1=Kenny |first1=Column |title=Arthur Griffith: More Zionist than Anti-Semite |journal=History Ireland |date=2016 |url=https://www.historyireland.com/volume-24/arthur-griffith-zionist-anti-semite/ |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1904 until his death, Griffith wrote virtually nothing which could be construed as antisemitic.<ref name=\"Maye, Brian 1997, p368\"/> Already in 1903, he had supported the candidature of the Jewish Albert Altman for election to Dublin Corporation.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kenny |first1=Colum |title=Arthur Griffith and Anti-Semitism |journal=History Ireland |date=2016 |url=https://www.historyireland.com/volume-24/arthur-griffith-anti-semitism/ |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> In 1909, he wrote a favourable article in ''Sinn F\u00e9in'' on the Jewish contribution to European civilisation, and in ''Nationality'' in 1915, he railed against the [[Irish Parliamentary Party|Irish Party]] for saying that Jews should be barred from public office.<ref name=McGee409/><ref name=Kenny1/>\n\nGriffith was a close friend of Jewish solicitor [[Michael Noyk]], who defended many IRA members in [[court martial|courts martial]] during the [[Irish War of Independence]], and served as an official in the [[First D\u00e1il]] Department of Finance and as a [[D\u00e1il Courts|D\u00e1il Court]] judge during the war.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jewish Dublin|first=Asher|last=Benson|isbn=978-1-906353-00-1|year=2007}}</ref> Other Jewish Friends included Dr Edward Lipman, Jacob Elyan and Dr [[Bethel Solomons]].<ref name=Kenny1/> Noyk and Solomons were among a group of friends who purchased a house for Griffith when he married.<ref name=Kenny1/><ref>Manus O'Riordan, [http://www.drb.ie/essays/citizens-of-the-republic-jewish-history-in-ireland Citizens of the Republic, Jewish History in Ireland], ''Dublin Review of Books'', Summer 2007</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Arthur Griffith}}\n* [https://digital.library.villanova.edu/Item/vudl:521344 Arthur Griffith, Michael Collins] (dual memorial volume) available from the Digital LIbrary@Villanova University\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/006519}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Samuel Young (Irish politician)|Samuel Young]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] Member of Parliament for [[East Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|East Cavan]]\n       |years  = 1918\u20131922}}\n{{s-non | reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new | Constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] Member of Parliament for [[North West Tyrone (UK Parliament constituency)|North West Tyrone]]\n |years  = 1918\u20131922\n}}\n{{s-non | reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n\n{{s-par|ni}}\n{{s-new|Parliament}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Fermanagh and Tyrone (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh and Tyrone]]\n | years = 1921\u20131922\n | with  = [[Sir Edward Archdale, 1st Baronet|Edward Archdale]] 1921\u20131929\n | with2 = [[William Coote]] 1921\u20131924\n | with3 = [[Se\u00e1n Milroy]] 1921\u20131925\n | with4 = [[William Thomas Miller]] 1921\u20131929\n | with5 = [[James Cooper (Northern Ireland politician)|James Cooper]] 1921\u20131929\n | with6 = [[Se\u00e1n O'Mahony]] 1921\u20131925\n | with7 = [[Thomas Harbison]] 1921\u20131929\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after = [[Sir Edward Archdale, 1st Baronet|Edward Archdale]]\n | after2 = [[William Coote]]\n | after3 = [[Se\u00e1n Milroy]]\n | after4 = [[William Thomas Miller]]\n | after5 = [[James Cooper (Northern Ireland politician)|James Cooper]]\n | after6 = [[Se\u00e1n O'Mahony]]\n | after7 = [[Thomas Harbison]]\n}}\n\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[East Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|East Cavan]]\n       |years  = 1918\u20131921}}\n{{s-non | reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Fermanagh and Tyrone (D\u00e1il constituency)|Fermanagh and Tyrone]]\n       |years  = 1921\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Alex Donnelly]]}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Cavan (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cavan]]\n       |years  = 1921\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Patrick Smith (politician)|Patrick Smith]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Justice and Equality|Minister for Home Affairs]]\n       |years  = 1919\u20131921}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Frank Aiken]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[George Noble Plunkett|Count Plunkett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]\n       |years  = 1921\u2013Jan 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[George Gavan Duffy]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[George Gavan Duffy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]\n       |years  = Jul 1922\u2013 Aug 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Michael Hayes (politician)|Michael Hayes]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]]\n       |years  = 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[W. T. Cosgrave]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = New position}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in#Vice-Presidents|Vice President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 1905\u20131908<br /><small>with [[John Sweetman]] (1905\u20131907)<br />with [[Bulmer Hobson]] (1907\u20131908)</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Bulmer Hobson]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[John Sweetman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in|President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 1911\u20131917}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = ?<br />[[Thomas Kelly (Sinn F\u00e9in politician)|Thomas Kelly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in#Vice-Presidents|Vice President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 1917\u20131922<br /><small>with [[Michael O'Flanagan]]</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Michael O'Flanagan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes||title=Arthur Griffith navigational boxes|list1=\n{{2nd Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{3rd Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{4th Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{1st Provisional Government of the Irish Free State}}\n{{Heads of government of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Foreign Affairs of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Justice of Ireland}}\n{{Sinn F\u00e9in}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Griffith, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glasnevin Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Early Sinn F\u00e9in TDs]]\n[[Category:Heads of Irish provisional governments]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Leaders of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 3rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1921\u20131925]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland for Fermanagh and Tyrone]]\n[[Category:Members of the Irish Republican Brotherhood]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Cavan constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Tyrone constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Foreign Affairs (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Justice (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:People of the Irish Civil War (Pro-Treaty side)]]\n[[Category:People of the Irish War of Independence]]\n[[Category:Political party founders]]\n[[Category:Sinn F\u00e9in MPs (pre-1921)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|Irish politician and writer, founder of Sinn Fein}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Arthur Griffith\n| nationality   = Irish\n| image         = Arthur Griffith.jpg\n| office        = [[President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]]\n| term_start    = 10 January 1922\n| term_end      = 12 August 1922\n| predecessor   = [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] <small>(As President of the Irish Republic)</small>\n| successor     = [[W. T. Cosgrave]]\n| office2       = Minister for Foreign Affairs\n| term_start2   = 26 August 1921\n| term_end2     = 9 January 1922\n| predecessor2  = [[George Noble Plunkett|Count Plunkett]]\n| successor2    = [[George Gavan Duffy]]\n| office3       = Minister for Home Affairs\n| term_start3   = 2 April 1919\n| term_end3     = 22 August 1921\n| predecessor3  = [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]\n| successor3    = [[Austin Stack]]\n| office4       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start4   = 1921\n| term_end4     = 1922\n| constituency4 = [[Cavan (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cavan]]\n| term_start5   = 1921\n| term_end5     = 1922\n| constituency5 = [[Fermanagh and Tyrone (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh and Tyrone]]\n| term_start6   = 1918\n| term_end6     = 1921\n| constituency6 = [[East Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|East Cavan]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1871|3|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1922|8|12|1871|3|31|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Dublin, Ireland\n| party         = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n| spouse        = Maud Sheehan\n| children      = 2\n|}}\n'''Arthur Joseph Griffith''' ({{lang-ga|Art Seosamh \u00d3 Gr\u00edobhtha}}; 31 March 1871 \u2013 12 August 1922) was an Irish writer, newspaper editor and politician who founded the political party [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. He led the Irish delegation at the negotiations that produced the 1921 [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]], and served as [[President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] from January 1922 until his death in August 1922.\n\nAfter a short spell in [[South Africa]], Griffith founded and edited the [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalist]] newspaper ''[[United Irishman|The United Irishman]]'' in 1899. In 1904, he wrote ''[[The Resurrection of Hungary|The Resurrection of Hungary: A Parallel for Ireland]]'', which advocated the withdrawal of Irish members from the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] and the setting up of the institutions of government at home, a policy that became known as {{lang|ga|Sinn F\u00e9in}} (ourselves). On 28 November 1905, he presented \"The Sinn F\u00e9in Policy\" at the first annual convention of his organisation, the National Council; the occasion is marked as the founding date of the Sinn F\u00e9in party. Griffith took over as president of Sinn F\u00e9in in 1911, but at that time the organisation was still small.\n\nGriffith was arrested following the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916, despite not having taken any part in it. On his release, he worked to build up Sinn F\u00e9in, which won a string of by-election victories. At the party's {{lang|ga|[[Ardfheis]]}} (annual convention) in October 1917, Sinn F\u00e9in became an unambiguously [[Irish republicanism|republican]] party, and Griffith resigned the presidency in favour of the 1916 leader [[\u00c9amon de Valera]], becoming vice-president instead. Griffith was elected as a member of parliament (MP) for [[East Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|East Cavan]] in a [[by-election]] in June 1918, and re-elected in the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 general election]], when Sinn F\u00e9in won a huge electoral victory over the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] and, refusing to take their seats at Westminster, set up their own constituent assembly, [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (Irish Republic)|D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]].<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Arthur-Griffith.D.1919-01-21/|title=Arthur Griffith|work=Oireachtas Members Database|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the D\u00e1il, Griffith served as Minister for Home Affairs from 1919 to 1921, and Minister for Foreign Affairs from 1921 to 1922. In September 1921, he was appointed chairman of the Irish delegation to negotiate a treaty with the British government. After months of negotiations, he and the other four delegates signed the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]], which created the [[Irish Free State]], but not as a republic. This led to a split in the D\u00e1il. After the Treaty was narrowly approved by the D\u00e1il, de Valera resigned as president and Griffith was elected in his place. The split led to the [[Irish Civil War]]. Griffith died suddenly in August 1922, two months after the outbreak of that war.\n\n==Family and early life==\nArthur Joseph Griffith was born at 61 Upper Dominick Street, [[Dublin]] on 31 March 1871,<ref name=birth>{{cite web|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/images/birth_returns/births_1871/03298/2208617.pdf|title=31st March 1871 - Birth of Arthur Griffith|work=Civil Records on Irish Genealogy Site|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> of distant Welsh lineage. His great-great-grandfather, William Griffith of Drws-y-coed Uchaf, [[Rhyd-ddu]], [[Caernarvonshire]] (1719-1782), was a farmer and supporter of the [[Moravian Church]] cause. His great grandfather, Griffith Griffith (b.1789), emigrated first to America and then to Ireland, where some of his sisters had settled in Dublin among the Moravian community there.<ref>R.T. Jenkins, ''The Moravian Brethren in North Wales'', (Hon. Soc. of Cymmrodorion, London, 1938, pp.82-6, 151-4; broadcast gan Karen Owen, Radio Cymru, ''Rhaglen Dei Tomos'', 24.02.2019</ref> A Roman Catholic,<ref name=\"Maye, Brian 1997, p368\">Maye, Brian: ''Arthur Griffith'', Dublin, Griffith College Publications, 1997, p. 368<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref> he was educated by the Irish [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]]. He worked for a time as a printer before joining the [[Gaelic League]], which was aimed at promoting the restoration of the [[Irish language]].\n\nHis father had been a printer on ''[[The Nation (Irish newspaper)|The Nation]]'' newspaper \u2014 Griffith was one of several employees locked out in the early 1890s due to a dispute with a new owner of the paper. The young Griffith was a member of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]] (IRB). He visited [[South Africa]] from 1897 to 1898, after the defeat and death of [[Charles Stewart Parnell]], whose more moderate views he had initially supported, and while he was recovering from [[tuberculosis]]. There he supported the [[Boers]] against British expansionism and was a strong admirer of [[Paul Kruger]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\nIn 1899, on returning to [[Dublin]], he co-founded the weekly ''[[United Irishman]]'' newspaper with his associate [[William Rooney]], who died in 1901. On 24 November 1910, Griffith married his fianc\u00e9e, Maud Sheehan, after a six-year engagement; they had a son and a daughter.<ref>Arthur Griffith by Owen Magee, 2015</ref>\n\nGriffith's fierce criticism of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]]'s alliance with the British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] was heavily influenced by the anti-Liberal rhetoric of [[Young Ireland]]er [[John Mitchel]]. Griffith also expressed a number of highly-controversial opinions. He defended [[antisemitic]] rioters in [[Limerick]], and denounced socialists and [[pacifism|pacifists]] as conscious tools of the [[British Empire]]. Griffith also supported movements seeking national independence from the British Empire in [[Egypt]] and [[India]], and wrote a highly-critical description of the British government action at [[Northern Ndebele people|Matabele]]. Despite his opposition to communism and socialism, he sometimes worked with [[James Connolly]], who also supported Irish nationalism.<ref>[http://www.historyireland.com/20th-century-contemporary-history/arthur-griffith-brian-maye-griffith-college-publications-25-isbn-0-9531611-0-2/ Review of Brian Maye's ''Arthur Griffith'' by Patrick Maume], ''History Ireland'', 6:1 (Spring 1998)</ref>\n\nIn September 1900, he established an organisation called ''[[Cumann na nGaedheal (1900)|Cumann na nGaedheal]]'' (\"Society of Gaels\"), to unite advanced nationalist and [[separatist]] groups and clubs. In 1903, he set up the National Council, to campaign against the visit to Ireland of [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|King Edward VII]] and his consort [[Alexandra of Denmark]].<ref>Irish Leaving cert history textbook; Movements for Political and Social Reform 1870\u20131914.</ref> In 1907, that organisation merged with the Sinn F\u00e9in League, which itself had been formed from an amalgamation of Cumann na nGaedheal and the Dungannon Clubs, to form what would become Sinn F\u00e9in.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boyce|first1=D. George|last2=O'Day|first2=Alan|authorlink1=D. G. Boyce|title=Ireland in Transition, 1867-1921|date=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1134320000|page=155|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=68JG1dTxUcgC&pg=PA155|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, after the ''United Irishman'' journal collapsed because of a libel suit, Griffith re-founded it under the title ''[[Sinn F\u00e9in (newspaper)|Sinn F\u00e9in]]''. It briefly became a daily in 1909 and survived until its suppression by the British government in 1914, after which Griffith became editor of the new nationalist journal, ''Nationality''.\n\n==Foundation of Sinn F\u00e9in==\nMost historians opt for 28 November 1905 as a founding date because it was on this date that Griffith first presented his 'Sinn F\u00e9in Policy'. In his writings, Griffith declared that the [[Act of Union 1800|Act of Union of Great Britain and Ireland in 1800]] was illegal and that, consequently, the Anglo-Irish dual monarchy that existed under [[Grattan's Parliament]] and the so-called ''[[Constitution of 1782]]'' were still in effect. Its first president was [[Edward Martyn]].\n\nThe fundamental principles of abstentionism on which Sinn F\u00e9in was founded were outlined in an article published in 1904, by Griffith called ''[[The Resurrection of Hungary]]'', in which, noting how in 1867 Hungary went from being ''part'' of the [[Austrian Empire]] to a separate co-equal kingdom in [[Austria-Hungary]]. Though not a [[monarchism|monarchist]] himself, Griffith advocated such an approach for the [[Anglo-Irish]] relationship, namely that Ireland should become a separate kingdom alongside Great Britain, the two forming a [[dual monarchy]] with a shared monarch but separate governments, as it was thought this solution would be more palatable to the British.<ref name=\"ResurrectionOfIreland\" /> This was similar to the policy of [[Henry Grattan]] a century earlier. However, this idea was never really embraced by later separatist leaders, especially [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]], and never came to anything, although [[Kevin O'Higgins]] toyed with the idea as a means of ending [[Partition of Ireland|partition]], shortly before his assassination in 1927.\n\nGriffith sought to combine elements of [[Charles Stewart Parnell|Parnellism]] with the traditional separatist approach; he saw himself not as a leader but as providing a strategy which a new leader might follow. Central to his strategy was parliamentary [[abstentionism|abstention]]: the belief that Irish [[Member of Parliament|MPs]] should refuse to attend the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] at [[Westminster]], but should instead establish a separate Irish parliament (with an administrative system based on local government) in Dublin.\n\nGriffith was a staunch [[Economic nationalism|economic nationalist]], he argued that nationalism was central to the fostering of economic growth. He often cited the works of German economist [[Friedrich List]].<ref name=\"ResurrectionOfIreland\">{{Cite book|title=The Resurrection of Ireland: The Sinn F\u00e9in Party 1916-1923|last=Laffan|first=Michael|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=223}}</ref>\n\nIn 1907, Sinn F\u00e9in unsuccessfully contested a by-election in [[North Leitrim (UK Parliament constituency)|North Leitrim]], where the sitting MP, one [[Charles Dolan (politician)|Charles Dolan]] of [[Manorhamilton]], [[County Leitrim]], had defected to Sinn F\u00e9in. At this time Sinn F\u00e9in was being infiltrated by the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]], who saw it as a vehicle for their aims; it had several local councillors (mostly in Dublin, including [[W. T. Cosgrave]]) and contained a dissident wing grouped from 1910 around the monthly periodical called ''Irish Freedom''. The IRB members argued that the aim of dual monarchism should be replaced by republicanism and that Griffith was excessively inclined to compromise with conservative elements (notably in his pro-employer position during the 1913\u20131914 [[Dublin Lockout]], when he saw the syndicalism of [[James Larkin]] as aimed at crippling Irish industry for Great Britain's benefit).\n\nIn 1911, he helped to found the [[Proportional Representation Society of Ireland]], believing that [[proportional representation]] would help to prevent animosity between unionists and nationalists in an independent Ireland.<ref>John Coakley and Michael Gallagher, ''Politics in the Republic of Ireland'' (Taylor & Francis, 2010), 113.</ref>\n\n==1916 Rising==\nIn 1916, rebels seized and took over a number of key locations in Dublin, in what became known as the [[Easter Rising]]. After its defeat, it was widely described both by British politicians and the Irish and British media as the \"Sinn F\u00e9in rebellion\", even though Sinn F\u00e9in had very limited involvement. When in 1917, surviving leaders of the rebellion were released from gaol (or escaped) they joined Sinn F\u00e9in ''en masse'', using it as a vehicle for the advancement of the republic. The result was a bitter clash between those original members who backed Griffith's concept of an Anglo-Irish dual monarchy and the new members, under [[\u00c9amon de Valera]], who wanted to achieve a republic. Matters almost led to a split at the party's Ard Fheis (conference) in October 1917.\n\nIn a compromise, it was decided to seek to establish a republic initially, then allow the people to decide whether they wanted a republic or a monarchy, subject to the condition that no member of Britain's royal house could sit on any prospective Irish throne.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Packenham|first1=Frank|title=\u00c9amon de Valera|date=1974|publisher=Arrow Books|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r7MMAQAAMAAJ&q=%22no+contemplation+in+it%22|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> At that Ard Fheis, Griffith resigned the presidency of Sinn F\u00e9in in favour of de Valera; he and [[Michael O'Flanagan|Fr. Michael O'Flanagan]] were elected Vice-Presidents. The leaders of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] (IPP) sought a rapprochement with Griffith over the British threat of [[conscription]], which both parties condemned, but Griffith refused unless the IPP embraced his more radical and subversive ideals, a suggestion which [[John Dillon]], a leader of the IPP rubbished as unrealistic, although it would ultimately mean the defeat and dissolution of the IPP after the election in December 1918.\n\n==War of Independence==\n[[File:Arthur Griffith 071022.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Griffith seen in July 1922, a month before his death]]\nIn May 1918, along with \u00c9amon de Valera and 72 other Sinn F\u00e9iners, Griffith was arrested on the pretext of involvement in the fictitious [[German Plot (Ireland)|German Plot]]. Griffith spent ten months interned in Gloucester jail, being released on 6 March 1919. Fr. O'Flanagan was left as Acting-President of Sinn F\u00e9in.<ref name=Carroll>{{Cite book|title=They Have Fooled You Again|last=Carroll|first=Denis|publisher=The Columba Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-78218-300-6|location=|pages=}}{{Page number missing|date=February 2019}}</ref>  Griffith was put forward as a Sinn F\u00e9in candidate for the [[1918 East Cavan by-election|East Cavan by-election]] on 20 June 1918.<ref>Maume, Patrick: ''The long Gestation, Irish Nationalist Life 1891\u20131918'' p. 207 (note 322), Gill & Macmillan (1999); {{ISBN|0-7171-2744-3}}</ref> Under the slogan \"Put him in to get him out,\" and was elected. and held the seat when Sinn F\u00e9in subsequently routed the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] at the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 general election]] with a commitment of [[abstentionism]] from the [[British House of Commons]].<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=1082|title=Arthur Griffith|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=1 June 2009}}</ref> Griffith was returned for  returned for both East Cavan and [[North West Tyrone (UK Parliament constituency)|Tyrone North West]].\n\nSinn F\u00e9in's MPs set up an Irish parliament, [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (1919-1922)|D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] and [[Irish Declaration of Independence|declared independence]] for the [[Irish Republic]]; the [[Irish War of Independence]] followed almost immediately. The dominant leaders in the D\u00e1il included \u00c9amon de Valera, [[President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] (1919\u201321), President of the Republic (1921\u20131922), and [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]], [[Minister for Finance (Ireland)|Minister for Finance]], head of the IRB and the [[Irish Republican Army]]'s Director of Intelligence.\n\nDuring de Valera's absence in the [[United States]] (1919\u201321) Griffith served as Acting President and gave regular press interviews. He was arrested at his house at 3am, on 26 November 1920, and later jailed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1920/nov/26/mr-arthur-griffith-arrest |title=MR. ARTHUR GRIFFITH (ARREST). (Hansard, 26 November 1920) |website=Hansard.millbanksystems.com |date=1920-11-26 |accessdate=2017-05-28}}</ref> Fr. O'Flanagan again taking over as acting leader until de Valera returned from America on 23 December.<ref name=Carroll/> Griffith was to spend the next seven months in Dublin's [[Mountjoy Prison]]. He was released on 30 June 1921 as peace moves got under way.\n\nIn Ireland, a [[1921 Irish elections|general election]] was held on 24 May 1921 and Griffith, while still in prison, headed the poll in the contested constituency of [[Fermanagh and Tyrone (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh and Tyrone]], and was returned unopposed for [[Cavan (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cavan]]. On 26 August 1921, Griffith was appointed [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] in the new Irish cabinet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1921-08-26/4/|title=THE NEW MINISTRY \u2013 D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2nd D\u00e1il) \u2013 Friday, 26 August 1921|access-date=19 March 2020|website=Houses of the Oireachtas|date=26 August 1921}}</ref>\n\n==Treaty negotiations and death==\n[[File:Arthur Griffith Grave.jpg|thumb|right|Griffith's grave in [[Glasnevin Cemetery]], Dublin]]\nIn September 1921, de Valera, President of the Republic, asked Griffith to head the delegation of Irish plenipotentiaries to negotiate with the British government. The delegates set up Headquarters in [[Hans Place]], London. After nearly two months of negotiations, on 5 December, the delegates decided in private conversation in their headquarters to sign the Treaty and recommened it the to D\u00e1il; negotiations closed at 2.20am on 6 December 1921. Griffith was the member of the treaty delegation most supportive of its eventual outcome, a compromise based on [[dominion]] status, rather than a republic. The Treaty [[Anglo-Irish Treaty D\u00e1il vote|was ratified by the D\u00e1il]] by 64 votes to 57 on 7 January 1922. On 9 January, de Valera stood down as President and sought re-election by the D\u00e1il, which he lost by a vote of 58 to 60.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1922-01-09/2/|title=RESIGNATION OF PRESIDENT \u2013 D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2nd D\u00e1il) \u2013 Monday, 9 January 1922|access-date=31 August 2019|website=Houses of the Oireachtas|date=9 January 1922}}</ref> Griffith then succeeded de Valera as President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1922-01-10/2/|title=ELECTION OF PRESIDENT \u2013 D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2nd D\u00e1il) \u2013 Tuesday, 10 January 1922|access-date=31 August 2019|website=Houses of the Oireachtas|date=10 January 1922}}</ref> A second ratification of the Treaty by the [[House of Commons of Southern Ireland]] followed shortly afterwards. Griffith was, however, to a great extent merely a figurehead as President of the [[Second D\u00e1il]] and his relations with Michael Collins, head of the new [[Provisional Government]], were somewhat tense.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nSuffering from overwork and strain after the long and difficult negotiations with the [[British government]], Griffith attended forty-one of the forty-two\nprovisional government meetings held between 23 June and 30 July, and the work involved in establishing the Free State government, he entered St. Vincent's Nursing Home, [[Leeson Street]], Dublin, during the first week of August 1922, following an acute attack of tonsillitis.<ref>{{cite book|last=Glandon|first=Virginia E.|title = Arthur Griffith and the Advanced-nationalist Press, Ireland, 1900\u20131922|publisher=P. Lang|year=1985|page=230|isbn=0-8204-0041-6}}</ref> He was confined to a room in St Vincent's by his doctors, who had observed signs of what they thought might be a [[subarachnoid hemorrhage]], but it was difficult to keep him quiet,<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Connor|first=Ulick|authorlink=|title=Michael Collins and the Troubles|publisher=W.W. Norton|year=1996|isbn=0-393-31645-9|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/michaelcollinst00ocon}}</ref> and he resumed his daily work in the government building. He had been about to leave for his office shortly before 10 am on 12 August 1922, when he paused to retie his shoelace and fell down unconscious. He regained consciousness, but collapsed again with blood coming from his mouth. Three doctors rendered assistance, but to no avail. Fr John Lee of the [[Marist Fathers]] administered [[extreme unction]], and Griffith expired as the priest recited the concluding prayer. The cause of death, [[cerebral haemorrhage]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/details-civil/c764409590352|title=General Registrar's Office|last=|first=|date=|website=IrishGenealogy.ie|publisher=|access-date=12 August 2017}}</ref> was also reported as being due to heart failure.<ref name=nyt19220813>{{Cite news|title=Arthur Griffith Dies Suddenly|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=13 August 1922|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/08/13/107066789.pdf}}</ref> He died at the age of 51, ten days before [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]' assassination in [[County Cork]]. He was buried in [[Glasnevin Cemetery]] four days later.\n\n==Posthumous commemoration==\nThe historian [[Diarmaid Ferriter]] considers that, though he had founded Sinn F\u00e9in, Griffith was 'quickly airbrushed' from Irish history. His widow had to beg his former colleagues for a pension, saying that he 'had made them all'. She considered that his grave plot was too modest and threatened to exhume his body. Only in 1968 was a plaque fixed on his former home.<ref>Ferriter, D. ''The Transformation of Ireland 1900\u20132000'' (Profile 2004) p. 260; {{ISBN|1-86197-307-1}}</ref>\n\n[[Griffith Barracks]] which is now [[Griffith College Dublin]] on [[South Circular Road, Dublin]], [[R102 road (Ireland)|Griffith Avenue]] in North Dublin, Griffith Park in [[Drumcondra, Dublin|Drumcondra]] and Arthur Griffith Park in [[Lucan, County Dublin]] are named after him. An obelisk erected in 1950 in the grounds of [[Leinster House]] commemorates Griffith, as well as [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]] and [[Kevin O'Higgins]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The OPW \u2013 a history of service|year=2006|publisher=The Office of Public Works|page=5|url=http://irishartsreview.com/irisartsrevi2002/pdf/2006/25503509.pdf.bannered.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120917014345/http://irishartsreview.com/irisartsrevi2002/pdf/2006/25503509.pdf.bannered.pdf|archivedate=17 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Claims of antisemitism==\nIn 1997, [[Simon Sebag Montefiore]] wrote an article in ''[[The Spectator]]'' which, he claimed, \"exposes the role of Sinn Fein's founder in an Irish persecution of Jews.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Montefiore |first1=Simon Sebag |title=Arthur Griffith, anti-Semite |url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/11th-october-1997/28/arthur-griffith-anti-semite |accessdate=7 February 2019 |work=[[The Spectator]] |date=11 October 1997 |pages=28\u201330 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> No such claim has been made in any biography of Griffith or history of early Sinn F\u00e9in before then, or immediately afterwards.<ref>{{cite book |last1=\u00d3 L\u00faing |first1=Se\u00e1n |title=Art \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa |date=1953 |publisher=S\u00e1irs\u00e9al agus Dill}}; {{cite book |last1=Colum |first1=Padraic |title=Arthur Griffith |url=https://archive.org/details/arthurgriffith0000colu |url-access=registration |date=1959 |publisher=Browne and Nolan}}; {{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Richard P. |title=Arthur Griffith and Non-Violent Sinn Fein |date=1974 |publisher=Anvil Books}}; {{cite book |last1=Laffan |first1=Michael |title=The Resurrection of Ireland: The Sinn F\u00e9in Party 1916-1923 |date=1999 |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>\n\nAs editor of the ''[[United Irishman]]'', Griffith took an [[Anti-Dreyfusard]] line, publishing articles signed by 'The Home Secretary' ([[Frank Hugh O'Donnell]]) that were anti-Semitic in tone, including one in 1899 that stated: \"I have in former years often declared that the Three Evil Influences of the century were the Pirate, the Freemason, and the Jew.\"<ref name=keogh>{{cite book|last=Keogh|first=Dermot|title=Jews in Twentieth-century Ireland: Refugees, Anti-semitism and the Holocaust|publisher=Cork University Press|year=1998|page=22|isbn=1-85918-150-3}}</ref> In 1904, the paper voiced support for the [[Limerick Boycott]], a boycott of Jewish businesses in Limerick organised by a local priest, declaring that \"the Jew in Limerick has not been boycotted because he is a Jew, but because he is a usurer.\" Griffith was apparently unaware that the Jews of Limerick had little or no involvement in money-lending or similar practices.<ref name=\"Maye, Brian 1997, p368\"/><ref name=McGee409>{{cite book |last1=McGee |first1=Owen |title=Arthur Griffith |date=2015 |publisher=Merrion Press |isbn=978-1-78537-009-0 |page=409 (fn 62)}}</ref> The ''United Irishman'' also published articles by [[Oliver St. John Gogarty]] that contained antisemitic sentiments. Such sentiments, however, were common in the Ireland of the time.<ref name=Kenny1>{{cite journal |last1=Kenny |first1=Column |title=Arthur Griffith: More Zionist than Anti-Semite |journal=History Ireland |date=2016 |url=https://www.historyireland.com/volume-24/arthur-griffith-zionist-anti-semite/ |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1904 until his death, Griffith wrote virtually nothing which could be construed as antisemitic.<ref name=\"Maye, Brian 1997, p368\"/> Already in 1903, he had supported the candidature of the Jewish Albert Altman for election to Dublin Corporation.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kenny |first1=Colum |title=Arthur Griffith and Anti-Semitism |journal=History Ireland |date=2016 |url=https://www.historyireland.com/volume-24/arthur-griffith-anti-semitism/ |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> In 1909, he wrote a favourable article in ''Sinn F\u00e9in'' on the Jewish contribution to European civilisation, and in ''Nationality'' in 1915, he railed against the [[Irish Parliamentary Party|Irish Party]] for saying that Jews should be barred from public office.<ref name=McGee409/><ref name=Kenny1/>\n\nGriffith was a close friend of Jewish solicitor [[Michael Noyk]], who defended many IRA members in [[court martial|courts martial]] during the [[Irish War of Independence]], and served as an official in the [[First D\u00e1il]] Department of Finance and as a [[D\u00e1il Courts|D\u00e1il Court]] judge during the war.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jewish Dublin|first=Asher|last=Benson|isbn=978-1-906353-00-1|year=2007}}</ref> Other Jewish Friends included Dr Edward Lipman, Jacob Elyan and Dr [[Bethel Solomons]].<ref name=Kenny1/> Noyk and Solomons were among a group of friends who purchased a house for Griffith when he married.<ref name=Kenny1/><ref>Manus O'Riordan, [http://www.drb.ie/essays/citizens-of-the-republic-jewish-history-in-ireland Citizens of the Republic, Jewish History in Ireland], ''Dublin Review of Books'', Summer 2007</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Patrick Maume, ''The Long Gestation'' (Gill & Macmillan, 1999).\n* There is a 2003 reprint of ''The Resurrection of Hungary'' with an introduction by Patrick Murray (University College Dublin Press).\n* [http://www.ucc.ie/celt/published/E900003-001/ The Treaty Debates on-line (Dec 1921&nbsp;\u2013 Jan 1922)]\n* [[Anthony J. Jordan]], ''Arthur Griffith with James Joyce & WB Yeats&nbsp;\u2013 \"Liberating Ireland\"'' [Westport Books 2013]\n* {{cite TIWW |article=Griffith, Arthur |page=98 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Arthur Griffith}}\n* [https://digital.library.villanova.edu/Item/vudl:521344 Arthur Griffith, Michael Collins] (dual memorial volume) available from the Digital LIbrary@Villanova University\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/006519}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Samuel Young (Irish politician)|Samuel Young]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] Member of Parliament for [[East Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|East Cavan]]\n       |years  = 1918\u20131922}}\n{{s-non | reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new | Constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] Member of Parliament for [[North West Tyrone (UK Parliament constituency)|North West Tyrone]]\n |years  = 1918\u20131922\n}}\n{{s-non | reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n\n{{s-par|ni}}\n{{s-new|Parliament}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Fermanagh and Tyrone (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh and Tyrone]]\n | years = 1921\u20131922\n | with  = [[Sir Edward Archdale, 1st Baronet|Edward Archdale]] 1921\u20131929\n | with2 = [[William Coote]] 1921\u20131924\n | with3 = [[Se\u00e1n Milroy]] 1921\u20131925\n | with4 = [[William Thomas Miller]] 1921\u20131929\n | with5 = [[James Cooper (Northern Ireland politician)|James Cooper]] 1921\u20131929\n | with6 = [[Se\u00e1n O'Mahony]] 1921\u20131925\n | with7 = [[Thomas Harbison]] 1921\u20131929\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after = [[Sir Edward Archdale, 1st Baronet|Edward Archdale]]\n | after2 = [[William Coote]]\n | after3 = [[Se\u00e1n Milroy]]\n | after4 = [[William Thomas Miller]]\n | after5 = [[James Cooper (Northern Ireland politician)|James Cooper]]\n | after6 = [[Se\u00e1n O'Mahony]]\n | after7 = [[Thomas Harbison]]\n}}\n\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[East Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|East Cavan]]\n       |years  = 1918\u20131921}}\n{{s-non | reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Fermanagh and Tyrone (D\u00e1il constituency)|Fermanagh and Tyrone]]\n       |years  = 1921\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Alex Donnelly]]}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Cavan (D\u00e1il constituency)|Cavan]]\n       |years  = 1921\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Patrick Smith (politician)|Patrick Smith]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Justice and Equality|Minister for Home Affairs]]\n       |years  = 1919\u20131921}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Frank Aiken]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[George Noble Plunkett|Count Plunkett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]\n       |years  = 1921\u2013Jan 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[George Gavan Duffy]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[George Gavan Duffy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]\n       |years  = Jul 1922\u2013 Aug 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Michael Hayes (politician)|Michael Hayes]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[President of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]]\n       |years  = 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[W. T. Cosgrave]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = New position}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in#Vice-Presidents|Vice President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 1905\u20131908<br /><small>with [[John Sweetman]] (1905\u20131907)<br />with [[Bulmer Hobson]] (1907\u20131908)</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Bulmer Hobson]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[John Sweetman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in|President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 1911\u20131917}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = ?<br />[[Thomas Kelly (Sinn F\u00e9in politician)|Thomas Kelly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in#Vice-Presidents|Vice President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 1917\u20131922<br /><small>with [[Michael O'Flanagan]]</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Michael O'Flanagan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes||title=Arthur Griffith navigational boxes|list1=\n{{2nd Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{3rd Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{4th Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{1st Provisional Government of the Irish Free State}}\n{{Heads of government of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Foreign Affairs of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Justice of Ireland}}\n{{Sinn F\u00e9in}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Griffith, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glasnevin Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Early Sinn F\u00e9in TDs]]\n[[Category:Heads of Irish provisional governments]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Leaders of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 3rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1921\u20131925]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland for Fermanagh and Tyrone]]\n[[C