BB schedule entry\n| date         = 3/13/2015\n| time         = 9:45 PM\n| w/l          = l\n| nonconf      = \n| homecoming   = \n| away         = \n| neutral      = yes\n| rank         = 23\n| opponent     = Xavier\n| opprank      = \n| site_stadium = Madison Square Garden\n| site_cityst  = New York, NY\n| gamename     = Semifinals\n| tv           = FS1\n| score        = 63\u201365\n| overtime     = \n| attend       = 15,194\n| record       = 21\u201310\n}}\n|-\n!colspan=9 style=\"background:#002147; color:white;\"| [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|<span style=\"color:white;\">NCAA Tournament</span>]]\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = 3/19/2015\n| time         = 9:57 PM\n| w/l          = w\n| nonconf      = yes\n| neutral      = yes\n| rank         = 22\n| seed        = 4 S\n| opponent     = [[2014\u201315 Eastern Washington Eagles men's basketball team|Eastern Washington]]\n| oppseed      = 13 S\n| site_stadium = [[Moda Center]]\n| site_cityst  = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland, OR]]\n| gamename     = Second round\n| tv           = [[NCAA March Madness (CBS/Turner)|truTV]]\n| score        = 84\u201374\n| attend       = 14,279\n| record       = 22\u201310\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = 3/21/2015\n| time         = 7:45 PM\n| w/l          = l\n| nonconf      = yes\n| neutral      = yes\n| rank         = 22\n| seed        = 4 S\n| opponent     = [[2014\u201315 Utah Utes men's basketball team|Utah]]\n| opprank      = 19\n| oppseed      = 5 S\n| site_stadium = Moda Center\n| site_cityst  = Portland, OR\n| gamename     = Third round\n| tv           = [[NCAA March Madness (CBS/Turner)|CBS]]\n| score        = 64\u201375\n| attend       = 17,370\n| record       = 22\u201311\n}}\n{{CBB schedule end|rank=|poll=[[AP Poll]]|timezone=[[Eastern Time Zone]]|region=S|regionname=South Region}}\n\nSource<ref>[http://www.guhoyas.com/sports/m-baskbl/sched/gu-m-baskbl-sched.html guhoyas.com Men's Basketball 2014-2015 Schedule]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://guhoyas.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/gu-m-baskbl-body.html Georgetown Hoyas Basketball]\n\n{{Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014-15 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team}}\n[[Category:Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball seasons]]\n[[Category:2014\u201315 Big East Conference men's basketball season|Georgetown]]\n[[Category:2014 in sports in Washington, D.C.|Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team]]\n[[Category:2015 in sports in Washington, D.C.|Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team]]\n[[Category:2015 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament participants|Georgetown]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n|sport        =Basketball\n|year         =2014\u201315\n|prev_year    =2013\u201314\n|next_year    =2015\u201316\n|team         =Georgetown Hoyas\n|image        = Georgetown Hoyas logo.svg\n|image_size   = \n|conference   =Big East\n|division     =\n|short_conf   =Big East\n|CoachRank    = \n|APRank       = 22\n|record       =22\u201311\n|conf_record  =12\u20136\n|head_coach   =[[John Thompson III]]\n|hc_year      = 11th\n|asst_coach1  =[[Kevin Broadus]]\n|ac1_year     = 6th\n|asst_coach2  =[[Tavaras Hardy]]\n|ac2_year     = 2nd\n|asst_coach3  =Kevin Sutton\n|ac3_year     = 2nd\n|stadium      =[[Capital One Arena|Verizon Center]]\n|champion     =\n|bowl         = [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n|bowl_result  = Third Round\n}}\n{{2014-15 Big East Conference men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''2014\u201315 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team''' represented [[Georgetown University]] in the [[2014\u201315 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. They were led by 11th year head coach [[John Thompson III]], were members of the [[Big East Conference]], and played their home games at the [[Capital One Arena|Verizon Center]]. They finished the season 22\u201311, 12\u20136 in Big East play to finish in a tie for second place. They advanced to the semifinals of the [[2015 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|Big East Tournament]] where they lost to Xavier. They received an at-large bid to the [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]] where they defeated Eastern Washington in the second round before losing in the third round to Utah.\n\n== Previous season ==\nThe [[2013\u201314 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|Hoyas]] finished the [[2014\u201315 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|previous season]] 18\u201315, 8\u201310 in Big East play, to finish in seventh place. They lost in the first round of the [[2014 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|Big East Tournament]] to [[DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball|DePaul]]. They were invited to the [[2014 National Invitation Tournament]], in which they lost in the second round to [[Florida State Seminoles men's basketball|Florida State]].\n\n==Departures==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n! Name !! Number !! Pos. !! Height !! Weight !! Year !! Hometown !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| [[Markel Starks]] || 5 || G || 6'2\" || 175 || Senior || [[Accokeek, Maryland|Accokeek, MD]] || Graduated\n|-\n| John Caprio || 25 || G || 6'6\" || 220 || Senior || [[North Caldwell, New Jersey|North Caldwell, NJ]] || Graduated\n|-\n| Moses Ayegba || 32 || C || 6'9\" || 247 || Senior || [[Kano|Kano, Nigeria]] || Transferred to [[Nebraska Cornhuskers men's basketball|Nebraska]]\n|-\n| Nate Lubick || 34 || F || 6'8\" || 219 || Senior || [[Southborough, Massachusetts|Southborough, MA]] || Graduated\n|}\n\n==Recruiting==\n{{Multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width = 200\n | image1 = 20130307 Paul White dunking.JPG\n | image2 = 20130308 LJ Peak.JPG\n | footer  = Incoming freshmen Paul White (left) and [[L. J. Peak]] (right) were teammates at [[Whitney M. Young Magnet High School]] in Chicago before coming to Georgetown.\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2013}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = [[Isaac Copeland]]\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|PF]]\n| hometown = Raleigh, NC\n| highschool = [[Brewster Academy]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 9\n| weight = 210\n| 40     =\n| commitdate = March 10, 2013\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 4\n| espn grade = 94\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = [[L. J. Peak]]\n| position = [[Small forward|SF]]\n| hometown = Gaffney, SC\n| highschool = [[Gaffney High School|Gaffney]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 5\n| weight = 190\n| 40     =\n| commitdate = July 2, 2013\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 4\n| espn grade = 89\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Paul White\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|PF]]\n| hometown = Chicago, IL\n| highschool = [[Whitney Young Magnet High School|Whitney Young]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 8\n| weight = 185\n| 40     =\n| commitdate = September 15, 2013\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 4\n| espn grade = 89\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Tre Campbell\n| position = [[Shooting guard|SG]]\n| hometown = Washington, D.C.\n| highschool = [[St. John's College High School|St. John's College]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 2\n| weight = 170\n| 40     =\n| commitdate = MAy 8, 2013\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 4\n| espn grade = 77\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               =\n| year             = 2014\n| rivals ref title = 2014 Georgetown Signees\n| scout ref title  = 2014 Georgetown Signees\n| espn ref title   = 2014 Georgetown Signees\n| rivals school    = georgetown\n| scout s          = 433\n| espn schoolid    = 46\n| scout overall    =\n| rivals overall   =\n| espn overall     =\n| accessdate       = October 27, 2013\n| bball            = yes\n}}\n\n==Season recap==\n\nSince the conclusion of [[2012\u201313 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|the previous season]], Georgetown had lost four players to graduation: Most notably, [[point guard]] [[Markel Starks]], who had finished the 2013\u20132014 season as the team's second-leading scorer, had graduated, as had [[Forward (basketball)|forward]] Nate Lubick and reserve [[Guard (basketball)|guard]] John Caprio. The fourth graduate was Moses Ayegba who, after three years as a reserve [[Center (basketball)|center]] at Georgetown, had opted to transfer to [[Nebraska Cornhuskers men's basketball|Nebraska]] to play out his final year of collegiate eligibility.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2014/04/24/nebraska-signs-georgetowns-moses-abraham-ayegba/8113927/ Anonymous, \"Nebraska signs Georgetown's Moses Abraham Ayegba,\" Associated Press, April 24, 2014, 4:08 p.m. EDT. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref>\n\nReturning for 2014\u20132015 were the team's leading scorer from 2013\u20132014, junior guard [[D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera]] \u2013 a shooting guard while Starks was on the team but taking on point guard duties this season \u2013 as well as junior guard Jabril Trawick, senior forward [[Mikael Hopkins]], sophomore [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] Reggie Cameron, and junior reserve center Bradley Hayes. Reserve forward Aaron Bowen, a [[Redshirt (sports)|redshirt]] senior the previous season, had a year of collegiate eligibility remaining due to a freshman season cut short by surgery, and, although he had the option of transferring elsewhere to play out his eligibility without sitting out a season, he opted to play at Georgetown in 2014\u20132015 as a fifth-year senior.<ref>[https://www.casualhoya.com/2014/11/7/7167261/georgetown-hoyas-player-profiles-aaron-bowen Anonymous, \"Georgetown Hoyas Player Profiles: Aaron Bowen,\" casualhoya.com, November 7, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> Two junior guards made the team as [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-ons]], David Allen for the third straight season and Riyan Williams, the son of former Georgetown great [[Reggie Williams (basketball, born 1964)|Reggie Williams]], who had walked on the previous season and had made the roster in January 2014. Senior center Tyler Adams, sidelined early in his [[2011\u201312 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|freshman season]] by [[heart arrhythmia]], spent the season on a medical hardship waiver that allowed him to continue at Georgetown on a scholarship without counting against the team's scholarship total. Relegated to the bench for another year, he made the most of the situation, acting as a ''de facto'' assistant coach, although he made a brief appearance on the court in Georgetown's final home game of the season.<ref name=kilgore20150306>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/his-basketball-career-cut-short-hoyas-tyler-adams-gets-a-final-day-on-court/2015/03/06/03878656-c43e-11e4-9ec2-b418f57a4a99_story.html Kilgore, Adam, \"Georgetown\u2019s Tyler Adams, his career cut short by heart ailment, gets one last start,\" washingtonpost.com, March 6, 2015.]</ref>\n\nMost notably, senior center [[Joshua Smith (basketball)|Joshua Smith]] returned. Criticism that he lacked maturity and a commitment to physical fitness and to playing winning basketball had dogged Smith earlier in his collegiate career when he spent parts of three seasons at [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]],<ref>[http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1822843-transfer-josh-smith-reportedly-cleared-to-play-for-georgetown-hoyas Conway, Tyler, \"Transfer Josh Smith Cleared to Play for Georgetown Hoyas,\" bleacherreport.com, October 23, 2013]</ref><ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/11/sports/la-sp-0112-ucla-basketball-fyi-20110112 Bolch, Ben, \"Ben Howland says Joshua Smith needs to grow up,\" latimes.com, January 11, 2011.]</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/georgetown-basketball-preview-josh-smith-is-a-reclamation-project-with-sizable-upside/2013/11/06/0ad6fc92-4722-11e3-bf0c-cebf37c6f484_story.html Clarke, Liz, \"Georgetown basketball preview: Josh Smith is a reclamation project with sizable upside,\" washingtonpost.com, November 6, 2013. Retrieved June 26, 2013=8.]</ref> and John Thompson III had suspended him the previous season for academic reasons after only 13 games with the Hoyas; that suspension had become an outright dismissal from the team shortly afterward when he continued to struggle in his classes, although the dismissal came with the understanding that he could return for the 2014\u20132015 season if his grades improved enough.<ref name=wang20141110>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/joshua-smith-is-georgetowns-big-man-back-on-campus/2014/11/10/90ab0f1c-65ed-11e4-ab86-46000e1d0035_story.html?noredirect=on Wang, Gene, \"Joshua Smith is Georgetown\u2019s big man (back) in the middle,\" washingtonpost.com, November 10, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> By the fall 2014 semester, he had resolved his academic problems, and Georgetown allowed him to rejoin the team for the 2014\u20132015 season.<ref name=wang20141110/> When suspended, he had been the 2013\u20132014 team's third-leading scorer and was a key part of Georgetown's offense, and his departure that season had led to a steep drop in the 2013\u20132014's teams fortunes.<ref name=wang20141110/> Although Smith's performance had declined noticeably during the last few games before his suspension, he and Smith-Rivera were the only returning Georgetown players who had averaged in double figures for the 2013\u20132014 season.<ref name=wang20141110/>  Arriving in the fall of 2014 30 pounds (13.6&nbsp;kg) lighter than the year before and having undergone an offseason fitness regimen, Smith again was expected to serve as the centerpiece of Georgetown's offense.<ref name=wang20141110/>\n\nFive freshmen \u2013 guard Tre Campbell, [[small forward]] [[L. J. Peak]], and forwards [[Isaac Copeland]], Paul White, and Trey Mourning \u2013 joined the team. Mourning was the son of former Georgetown and [[National Basketball Association]] great [[Alonzo Mourning]], and his arrival marked the fourth time in Georgetown basketball history that the son of a former player had joined the team.\n\n===Nonconference schedule===\n\nGeorgetown began its season with three wins at the [[Capital One Arena|Verizon Center]], defeating [[2014\u201315 St. Francis Brooklyn Terriers men's basketball team|St. Francis Brooklyn]], [[2014\u201315 Texas A&M\u2013Corpus Christi Islanders men's basketball team|Texas A&M\u2013Corpus Christi]], and [[2014\u201315 Robert Morris Colonials men's basketball team|Robert Morris]]. Facing St. Francis Brooklyn in his first game as a Hoya, L. J. Peak went 9-for-9 from the field, including a three-pointer, and 4-for-8 from the free-throw line to finish with 23 points, while Jabril Trawick added 11 points, Joshua Smith \u2013 returning to action for the first time since January 4, 2014 \u2013 scored 10, and Mikael Hopkins grabbed 10 rebounds.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588323 Anonymous, \"Peak lifts Georgetown past St. Francis 83-62,\" Associated Press, November 15, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> Against Texas A&M\u2013Corpus Christi four days later, Smith had the first [[double-double]] of his Georgetown career, scoring 20 points and pulling down 12 rebounds, and Aaron Bowen came off the bench for 13 points and five steals, while Hopkins scored 12 points and Peak 10.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588332 Anonymous, \"Georgetown breaks away from Texas A&M-CC 78-62,\" Associated Press, November 18, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref><ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588332 Texas A&M\u2013CC vs. Georgetown \u2013 Box Score \u2013 November 18, 2014 \u2013 ESPN]</ref> Smith had another double-double in the Robert Morris game, scoring 22 points and grabbing 11 rebounds against the Colonials, and D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera had his first double-figure outing of the season as he and Peak scored 12 points each, while Hopkins pulled down 10 rebounds and scored six points.<ref name=ap20141122>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588338 Anonymous, \"Smith leads Georgetown past Robert Morris 80-66,\" Associated Press, November 22, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref><ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588338 Robert Morris vs. Georgetown \u2013 Box Score \u2013 November 22, 2014 \u2013 ESPN]</ref> Robert Morris junior guard Rodney Pryor, who two years later would play for Georgetown during the [[2016\u201317 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|2016\u20132017 season]], came off the bench for a team-high 16 points for the Colonials.<ref name=ap20141122/>\n\nNext, the Hoyas left the [[United States]] to play in the [[Battle 4 Atlantis]], an annual tournament held at [[Atlantis Paradise Island]] on [[Paradise Island]] in [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]] in the [[Bahamas]]. In the tournament's opening quarterfinal round, they faced their first ranked opponent of the season, No. 18 [[2014\u201315 Florida Gators men's basketball team|Florida]]. It was the first time the teams had met since [[2012\u201313 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|November 2012]], when their game was canceled after the first half due to condensation on the court and never completed, and it was the first game they completed against one another since [[2005\u201306 Florida Gators men's basketball team|Florida's 2006 national championship team]] knocked [[2005\u201306 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|the Hoyas]] out of the [[2006 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2006 NCAA Tournament]].<ref name=ap20141126>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588345 Anonymous, \"Georgetown edges No. 18 Florida in OT of Battle 4 Atlantis quarters,\" Associated Press, November 27, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> The game was a wild one that saw 21 lead changes.<ref name=ap20141126/> The Hoyas held the Gators to 36 percent shooting from the field,<ref name=ap20141126/> and although no Hoya scored more than six points in the first half, Georgetown went into the locker room at halftime with a 31\u201327 lead.<ref name=ap20141126/> Joshua Smith was called for two [[flagrant foul]]s during the game, one of which allowed Florida senior forward Jacob Kurtz to sink one of two free throws and give Florida a 44\u201342 lead with 7:07 left in regulation.<ref name=ap20141126/> Jabril Trawick fouled out with 34.1 seconds left in regulation, but shortly afterward the Hoya defense collapsed on Florida redshirt junior guard Eli Carter to prevent him from scoring, and the second half ended with the teams tied 53\u201353.<ref name=ap20141126/> In overtime, Gator sophomore guard [[Kasey Hill]] completed a three-point play with 11.5 seconds remaining to put Florida ahead 65\u201364, but D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera scored on a jumper with 3.4 seconds left to give Georgetown a 66\u201365 upset win.<ref name=ap20141126/> The game continued a streak that made 2014\u20132015 the first season since 1949-1950 that Florida had not scored at least 70 points in any of its first four games.<ref name=ap20141126/> Smith-Rivera had a game-high 17 points, while Paul White had his first double-digit game as a Hoya with 10 points and Jabril Trawick also scored 10 before fouling out.<ref name=ap20141126/>\n\nGeorgetown advanced to the semifinals to meet an even more challenging opponent, No. 2 [[2014\u201315 Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball team|Wisconsin]], which had defeated [[2014\u201315 UAB Blazers men's basketball team|UAB]] easily in the first round. The game was the first meeting between Wisconsin and Georgetown since [[1981\u201382 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|December 28, 1982]].<ref name=ap20141127>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400608870 Anonymous, \"No. 2 Badgers edge Georgetown in Battle 4 Atlantis semifinals,\" Associated Press, November 27, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> The Hoyas made their first six shots and by halfway through the first half were shooting 61 percent from the field<ref name=ap20141127/> and leading 19\u201316;<ref name=playbyplay20141127>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/playbyplay?gameId=400608870 Georgetown vs. Wisconsin \u2013 Play-by-Play \u2013 November 27, 2014 \u2013 ESPN]</ref> Georgetown led for all but 56 seconds of the first half,<ref name=ap20141127/> but Wisconsin led 35\u201334 at halftime.<ref name=ap20141127/> Wisconsin fell behind in the second half, the first time all season the Badgers had trailed in the second half of a game,<ref name=ap20141127/> and Georgetown built a lead of nine points, 53\u201344, with 11:36 left to play.<ref name=ap20141127/><ref name=playbyplay20141127/> But Georgetown missed eight of its last 10 shots while the Badgers went on a decisive 22\u20136 run<ref name=ap20141127/> \u2013 during which Badger redshirt senior forward [[Duje Dukan]] scored all eight of his points in the game over a stretch of 80 seconds<ref name=ap20141127/><ref name=playbyplay20141127/> \u2013 to pull ahead 62\u201359 with 4:27 left to play<ref name=playbyplay20141127/> and 66\u201359 with 1:53 remaining.<ref name=playbyplay20141127/> D'Vauntes Smith Rivera, who had made all five of his previous three-point attempts, missed his last one, a potential game-tying shot which rimmed out as time expired, and, although Georgetown held the lead for all but 9 minutes 20 seconds of the game,<ref name=ap20141127/> Wisconsin came away with a 68\u201365 win and advanced to play [[2014\u201315 Oklahoma Sooners men's basketball team|Oklahoma]] in the tournament's championship game.<ref name=ap20141127/> The game saw 29 turnovers, 15 of them Georgetown's,<ref name=ap20141127/> and Wisconsin took decisive advantage of free-throw opportunities, going 13-for-18 (72.2 percent) from the line to Georgetown's 1-for-2.<ref name=ap20141127/> Smith-Rivera had a game-high 29 points,<ref name=ap20141127/> and Joshua Smith was the only other Hoya to score in double digits with 10 points.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400608870 Georgetown vs. Wisconsin \u2013 Box Score \u2013 November 27, 2014 \u2013 ESPN]</ref>\n\nGeorgetown moved on to the third-place game, meeting Big East rival [[2014\u201315 Butler Bulldogs men's basketball team|Butler]], which had beaten [[2014\u201315 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina]] in the quarterfinals and lost to Oklahoma in its semifinal game. Although NCAA rules ordinarily precluded two teams from the same conference from playing in the same early-season tournament, Butler received a waiver to play in the Battle 4 Atlantis because it did not decide to join the new Big East Conference until after accepting an invitation to the tournament.<ref name=ap20141128>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400608897 Anonymous, \"Butler beats Georgetown for 3rd place at Battle 4 Atlantis,\" Associated Press, November 28, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> From the field, Butler had shot 49-for-119 (41.2 percent) in the tournament,<ref name=ap20141128/> including weak shooting early in the Georgetown game, but then the Bulldogs began making shots, pulling out to a 21\u201313 lead that was the first time in school history they ever had led the Hoyas by more than seven points,<ref name=ap20141128/> and shooting 9-for-11 during one stretch in the second half.<ref name=ap20141128/> Butler prevailed 64\u201358, Georgetown's first loss to Butler in four meetings all-time between the schools.<ref name=ap20141128/> Against the Bulldogs, Isaac Copeland scored in double figures for the first time in his collegiate career, shooting 7-for-10 from the field and scoring 16 points, while Paul White added 13, and D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera finished with 12.<ref name=ap20141128/> The Hoyas had been called for at least 20 fouls in all three games they played in the Bahamas<ref name=ap20141128/> and were outscored 49-34 from the free-throw line;<ref name=ap20141128/> they had seen all three of their Battle 4 Atlantis games decided in the final minute and two of them on the final shot,<ref name=ap20141128/> and they went 1\u20132 and finished in fourth place in the 2014 Battle 4 Atlantis.\n\nAfter nine days off, the Hoyas opened a four-game homestand at the Verizon Center that began with an easy win over [[2014\u201315 Towson Tigers men's basketball team|Towson]] in which five Hoyas scored in double figures, with D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera finishing with a game-high 16 points, Paul White with 14 \u2013 including 4-of-5 shooting from three-point range \u2013 Joshua Smith with 12, Jabril Trawick with 11, and Isaac Copeland with 10.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588362 Anonymous, \"Georgetown cruises past Towson 78-46,\" Associated Press, December 7, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> It was Georgetown's first appearance in the annual [[BB&T Classic]]. Three days later, they hosted No. 10 [[2014\u201315 Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball team|Kansas]], their third ranked opponent of the season. During warm-ups, the national anthem, and pregame handshakes, the entire Georgetown roster wore black T-shirts emblazoned with \"I CAN\u2032T BREATHE\" in white lettering, which Joshua Smith explained to reporters was an expression of sympathy to the family of [[Death of Eric Garner|Eric Garner]], whose death while being arrested by [[New York City]] police officers in July 2014 was a matter of national controversy in the United States after a [[grand jury]] declined to [[Indictment|indict]] the officers involved.<ref name=ap20141211>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400585733 Anonymous, \"Brannen Greene, No. 10 Kansas prevail over Georgetown,\" Associated Press, December 11, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> Entering the game \u2013 the return visit for a home-and-home series in which Georgetown had traveled to play Kansas the previous season \u2013 the Jayhawks were 6\u20131 and had won five games in a row.<ref name=ap20141211/> The game had no flow, with 33 turnovers and 58 free throws taken by the two teams combined,<ref name=ap20141211/> and both Jayhawk sophomore guard Brannen Greene and Georgetown's Mikael Hopkins had four fouls by midway through the second half.<ref name=ap20141211/> Neither of the teams\u2032 leading scorers \u2013 [[Perry Ellis (basketball)|Perry Ellis]] for Kansas and D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera for Georgetown \u2013 had a good offensive performance, Ellis going 4-for-15 (26.7 percent) and Smith-Rivera 3-for-15 (20.0 percent) from the field.<ref name=ap20141211/> Brannen Greene scored a career-high 19 points for Kansas, 16 of them in the second half,<ref name=ap20141211/> but Joshua Smith led all scorers with 20 points, while L. J. Peak had 18 and Paul White and Smith-Rivera contributed 10 each.<ref name=ap20141211/> Jabril Trawick suffered a [[bone bruise]] in a collision with Greene during the game.<ref name=ap20141211/> A key officiating decision came with 18 seconds left to play and Kansas leading 71\u201367, when the ball went out of bounds after Isaac Copeland missed a three-pointer and the referees could not determine whose possession it was; they decided to call it a [[jump ball]], which, because of the alternating possession rule, gave the Jayhawks the ball.<ref name=ap20141211/> Greene promptly drew a foul by Copeland and made both free throws to give Kansas a 73\u201367 lead with 16 seconds left.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/playbyplay?gameId=400585733 Kansas vs. Georgetown  \u2013 Play-by-Play \u2013 December 10, 2014 \u2013 ESPN]</ref> The Jayhawks hung on for a 75\u201370 victory.<ref name=ap20141211/>\n\nThe homestand continued with an easy win over [[2014\u201315 Radford Highlanders men's basketball team|Radford]] in which Georgetown's bench players shined, scoring 42 points, with Aaron Bowen leading the way with a game-high and career-high 16 points and Paul White adding 12.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588369 Anonymous, \"Georgetown reserves sink Radford 76-49,\" Associated Press, December 13, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> [[2014\u201315 Charlotte 49ers men's basketball team|Charlotte]] visited a week later and lost a much closer game in which the Hoyas had to turn back a last-second 49ers upset bid.<ref name=ap20141220>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588378 Anonymous, \"Georgetown escapes with 81-78 win over Charlotte,\" Associated Press, December 20, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> In a balanced Georgetown attack, L. J. Peak led all scorers with 18 points, D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera had 13, Joshua Smith scored 12, and Jabril Trawick had  a double-double with 11 points and 10 rebounds, while Aaron Bowen came off the bench to add another 11 points.<ref name=ap20141220/><ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588378 Charlotte vs. Georgetown  \u2013 Box Score \u2013 December 20, 2014 \u2013 ESPN]</ref>\n\nA week later, Georgetown rounded out its non-conference schedule by visiting [[Madison Square Garden]] to meet [[2014\u201315 Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball team|Indiana]] in the Indeed Invitational.<ref name=ap20141227>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588388 Anonymous, \"Smith-Rivera leads Georgetown over Indiana,\" Associated Press, December 27, 2014. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> Despite getting in early foul trouble, Joshua Smith played a key role in the Hoyas\u2032 overtime win over the Hoosiers, scoring 14 points, while D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera scored a game-high 29, Aaron Bowen came off the bench to score 22 \u2013 a new career high for him \u2013 on 10-for-13 (76.9 percent) shooting from the field, and Jabril Trawick contributed 12.<ref name=ap20141227/><ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588388 Georgetown vs. Indiana \u2013 Box Score \u2013 December 27, 2014 \u2013 ESPN]</ref>  For the second season a row, the Hoyas finished their non-conference schedule with a record of 8\u20133. All three of their losses had come against teams either ranked at the time of the game or, in the case of Butler, soon afterward.<ref name=ap20141211/>\n\n===Conference schedule===\n\nThe [[Associated Press Poll]] ranked the Hoyas No. 25 at the end of December \u2013 their first national ranking since the final poll of the [[2012\u201313 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|2012-2013 season]]<ref name=fendrich20150103>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588402 Fendrich, Howard, \"Freshmen lead No. 25 Hoyas past Creighton 76-61,\" Associated Press, January 3, 2015. Retrieved July 2, 2018]</ref> \u2013 just in time for the Big East Conference season to begin with a full slate of five games on December 31, 2014. Georgetown \u2013 picked pre-season by the Big East's coaches for the second season in a row to finish second in the conference<ref name=wang20141110/> \u2013 opened the season with a visit to [[2014\u201315 Xavier Musketeers men's basketball team|Xavier]], where D'Vauntes Smith Rivera, who entered the game as the conference's fifth-leading scorer, was booed throughout the game because Xavier had recruited him heavily and he had chosen Georgetown instead.<ref name=ap20150101>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588398 Anonymous, \"Jalen Reynolds helps Xavier upset No. 25 Georgetown,\" Associated Press, January 1, 2015. Retrieved July 1, 2018]</ref> Although the Hoyas held the Musketeers 11 points below their season scoring average,<ref name=ap20150101/> Xavier also held Georgetown to its lowest point total of the season,<ref name=ap20150101/> and Xavier won 70\u201353 in an upset despite 18 points by Smith-Rivera and 10 by Joshua Smith.<ref name=ap20150101/>\n\nThe Hoyas returned to the Verizon Center and began 2015 with two wins, beating [[2014\u201315 Creighton Bluejays men's basketball team|Creighton]] and [[2014\u201315 Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball team|Marquette]]. In the Creighton game, with the Hoyas wearing pink shoelaces for Georgetown's second annual Men Against Breast Cancer game,<ref name=fendrich20150103/> Joshua Smith scored 14 points and Jabril Trawick added 12,<ref name=fendrich20150103/> but three freshman \u2013 L. J. Peak with 14 points, Tre Campbell with 13, and Paul White with 10 \u2013 combined for 37 of Georgetown's 76 points, including one stretch in which they scored 25 of 29 points, 13 of them in a row.<ref name=fendrich20150103/> It was the first time Campbell scored in double figures in a college game and the first time three Georgetown freshmen scored in double figures in the same game since [[2004\u201305 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|January 18, 2005]], when [[Jeff Green (basketball)|Jeff Green]], [[Roy Hibbert]], and [[Jonathan Wallace]] had each scored 12<ref name=fendrich20150103/> in a loss at [[2004\u201305 Syracuse Orange men's basketball team|Syracuse]]. By the time the Hoyas hosted Marquette, they had fallen back out of the Top 25 thanks to the loss at Xavier,<ref name=white20150106>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588404 White, Joseph, \"Smith has 12 and 10; Georgetown tops Marquette 65-59,\" Associated Press, January 6, 2015. Retrieved July 2, 2018]</ref> but they overcame their own cold shooting streak and a late surge by the Golden Eagles to win, thanks in part to 15 points by D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera, a double-double (12 points and 10 rebounds) by Joshua Smith, 13 points by L. J. Peak, and 12 by Jabril Trawick.<ref name=white20150106/>\n\nWith a conference record of 2\u20131, Georgetown went on the road to visit [[2014\u201315 Providence Friars men's basketball team|Providence]] and [[2014\u201315 DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball team|DePaul]]. They lost to Providence in overtime, with D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera scoring 15 points,<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588409 Anonymous, \"Henton, Dunn spark Providence past Georgetown 60-57 in OT,\" Associated Press, January 10, 2015. Retrieved July 3, 2018]</ref><ref name=boxscore20150110>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588409 Georgetown vs. Providence \u2013 Box Score \u2013 January 10, 2015 \u2013 ESPN]</ref> Joshua Smith recording another double-double with 15 points and 12 rebounds,<ref name=boxscore20150110/> and Paul White scoring 11 points off the bench,<ref name=boxscore20150110/> but recovered to beat [[2014\u201315 DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball team|DePaul]] \u2013 the team which upset them in the first round of the [[2014 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|previous season's Big East Tournament]] \u2013 for the 15th time in the past 16 meetings. Against the Blue Demons, D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera scored a game-high 25 points \u2013 including six of eight free throws he attempted in the final minute, part of a 26-for-32 (81.3 percent) Georgetown performance at the free-throw line \u2013 and Jabril Trawick added 11.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588414 Anonymous, \"Georgetown downs DePaul 78-72,\" Associated Press, January 14, 2015. Retrieved July 3, 2018]</ref> The Hoyas then returned home to meet Butler \u2013 which had beaten them in November during the Battle 4 Atlantis, then risen to as high as No. 15 in the AP Poll in December before falling back out of the AP Top 25 \u2013 for the first conference game of the season between the teams. Bulldog redshirt junior forward [[Roosevelt Jones]] scored a career-high 28 points, and the lead seesawed back and forth ten times in the final 8:48 of the game,<ref name=ap20150117>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588419 Anonymous, \"Georgetown beats Butler in final seconds 61-59,\" Associated Press, January 17, 2015. Retrieved July 3, 2018]</ref> but Isaac Copeland hit a three-pointer in the final seconds to give Georgetown the lead<ref name=ap20150119>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588423 Anonymoua, \"Georgetown smothers No. 4 Villanova in 20-point upset,\" Associated Press, January 21, 2015. Retrieved July 3, 2018]</ref> and D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera \u2013 who led the Hoyas with 14 points \u2013 preserved a Hoya victory by blocking Jones's final layup.<ref name=ap20150117/> Copeland, Joshua Smith, and Jabril Trawick scored 10 points each against the Bulldogs.<ref name=ap20150117/>\n\nNext to visit the Verizon Center was No. 4 [[2014\u201315 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball team|Villanova]], Georgetown's highest-ranked opponent since a meeting with No. 1 [[2012\u201313 Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball team|Indiana]] in [[2012\u201313 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|November 2012]]. At 17\u20131 overall and 4\u20131 in the Big East, the Wildcats had won four in a row since suffering their only loss of the season in an overtime game at [[2014\u201315 Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball team|Seton Hall]]<ref name=ap20150119/> 16 days earlier. It was a physical game, with the teams combining for 50 fouls.<ref name=ap20150119/> The Hoyas forced 17 Wildcat turnovers and held Villanova to 34 percent shooting from the field;<ref name=ap20150119/> the Wildcats shot 2-for-10 from three-point range during the first half and scored only two points off fast breaks during the entire game.<ref name=ap20150119/> Georgetown, in contrast, shot 60 percent from the field in the first half and pulled away early, holding Villanova scoreless for over seven minutes during a 17\u20130 Hoya scoring run that built a 30\u201311 Georgetown lead, and Georgetown went into the locker room ahead 42\u201320 at halftime.<ref name=ap20150119/> The Hoyas led by as many as 26 points in the second half.<ref name=ap20150119/> Villanova junior guard [[Ryan Arcidiacono]], who finished with 16 points, hit three three-pointers that helped the Wildcats close to 62\u201350 with eight minutes to play while Jabril Trawick sat on the bench for several minutes after getting hit in the eye, but Georgetown then went on a 6\u20130 run to open up a 68\u201350 lead. Villanova junior forward [[Daniel Ochefu]], coming off a career-high 21 points against [[2014\u201315 Penn Quakers men's basketball team|Pennsylvania]] two days earlier, scored only four points before fouling out with 4:13 remaining in the game. The Hoyas shot 51 percent from the field for the game and won 78\u201358.<ref name=ap20150119/> D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera, who had been announced as Big East Player of the Week earlier in the day,<ref name=ap20150119/> and Isaac Copeland each had 17 points \u2013 a career high for Copeland \u2013 to lead all scorers,<ref name=ap20150119/> while Jabril Trawick added 10 points and Joshua Smith had nine points and eight rebounds.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588423 Villanova vs. Providence \u2013 Box Score \u2013 January 17, 2015 \u2013 ESPN]</ref> Georgetown's 20-point upset put the Hoyas in first place in the Big East at 4\u20131, a half-game ahead of 4\u20132 Villanova,<ref name=ap20150119/> and the Georgetown student section stormed the court in celebration.<ref name=ap20150119/> The Hoyas stretched their winning streak to four games five days later with an overtime victory at Marquette, featuring a balanced attack in which D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera had 19 points including five three-pointers, Joshua Smith recorded another double-double with 18 points and 15 rebounds, Isaac Copeland scored 17 points, and Mikael Hopkins added 13, while Tre Campbell and Aaron Bowen both came off the bench to score in double figures, Campbell finishing with 14 points and Bowen with 11.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588429 Anonymous, \"Georgetown wins in OT, 95-85 over Marquette,\" Associated Press, January 24, 2015. Retrieved July 3, 2018]</ref>\n\nGeorgetown returned to the AP Top 25 after a three-week absence, ranked No. 21 in time for a return to the Verizon Center and the second meeting with Xavier of the season.<ref name=ap20150127>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588432 Anonymous, \"Xavier completes season sweep of No. 21 Georgetown,\" Associated Press, January 27, 2015. Retrieved July 3, 2018]</ref> L. J. Peak, who had injured his left ankle in the Marquette game, sat out the first five minutes, allowing Isaac Copeland to make his first collegiate start.<ref name=ap20150127/> D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera scored 13 points,<ref name=ap20150127/> Peak had 12, and Joshua Smith contributed 10,<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588432 Xavier vs. Georgetown \u2013 Box Score \u2013 January 27, 2015 \u2013 ESPN Retrieved July 3, 2018]</ref> but the Hoyas shot only 39 percent from the field and committed a season-high 17 turnovers,<ref name=ap20150131>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588440 Anonymous, \"Smith-Rivera leads No. 21 Hoyas past cold Creighton 67-40,\" Associated Press, January 31, 2015. Retrieved July 3, 2018]</ref> six of them by Jabril Trawick, who started despite suffering a bruised right thigh against Marquette.<ref name=ap20150127/> Xavier held Georgetown without a field goal for more than 11 minutes in the first half, and Georgetown's 16 points in the half were its fewest first-half points since it scored 16 in the first half of a game against [[2012\u201313 Tennessee Volunteers men's basketball team|Tennessee]] in [[2012\u201313 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|November 2012]].<ref name=ap20150127/> Georgetown had another scoring drought of over three minutes in the second half,<ref name=ap20150127/> and Xavier held Georgetown to only 53 points for the game, tying the Hoyas\u2032 season low set in the game at Xavier on January 3.<ref name=ap20150131/> The Musketeers won 66\u201353, sweeping the season series with Georgetown and snapping their own road losing streak of five games dating back to [[2013\u201314 Xavier Musketeers men's basketball team|the previous season]]<ref name=ap20150127/> \u2013 Xavier's longest road losing streak since an eight-game skid across two seasons in 1987.<ref name=ap20150127/> Georgetown's winning streak ended at four, dropping the Hoyas into second place in the Big East at 6\u20133, albeit only percentage points behind Villanova and [[2014\u201315 Providence Friars men's basketball team|Providence]], both 5\u20132 on the season.<ref name=ap20150127/> However, the Hoyas bounced back to close out January with a dominating win against last-place [[2014\u201315 Creighton Bluejays men's basketball team|Creighton]] in which no Creighton player scored in double figures and at one point the Bluejays went scoreless for 17 minutes 18 seconds.<ref name=ap20150131/> Georgetown held the Bluejays to 40 points and 20.8 percent shooting from the field,<ref name=ap20150131/> the lowest shooting percentage by a Big East team since [[2013\u201314 Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball team|Marquette]] shot 18.9 percent against [[2013\u201314 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]] on November 16, 2013,<ref name=ap20150131/> and the lowest in a Big East game since [[2007\u201308 West Virginia Mountaineers men's basketball team|West Virginia]] shot 20 percent against [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati]] in the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|original Big East]] on January 30, 2008.<ref name=ap20150131/>\n\nDropping to No. 24 in the AP Poll, the Hoyas began February by suffering a loss at home to Providence, which used a 20-6 run in the second half \u2013 with Georgetown going without a field goal for the final 7:41 of the game \u2013 to fuel a come-from-behind win that broke a 31-road-game Providence losing streak against ranked teams and a seven-game Hoya winning streak at home against the Friars.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588445 Anonymous, \"Ben Bentil helps Providence rally, take out No. 24 Georgetown,\" Associated Press, February 5, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> The Friars completed a season sweep of the Hoyas despite 21 points by D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera, 10 by Joshua Smith, and Tre Campbell and Isaac Copeland coming off the bench to score 10 each.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588445 Providence vs. Georgetown \u2013 Box Score \u2013 February 4, 2015 \u2013 ESPN Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> The Hoyas then traveled to [[Philadelphia]] for a rematch with Villanova, now ranked No. 7 and sporting a 21\u20132 record overall and 8\u20132 in the Big East, before a large crowd at the [[Wells Fargo Center (Philadelphia)|Wells Fargo Center]].<ref name=ap20150207>[\nhttp://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588449 Anonymous, \"No. 7 Villanova avenges earlier loss to No. 24 Georgetown,\" Associated Press, February 7, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> The Wildcats wore [[1984\u201385 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball team|1985 throwback uniforms]] in celebration of Villanova's upset triumph 30 years earlier over the [[1984-85 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|1984\u20131985 Hoyas]] in the [[1985 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|1985 NCAA Tournament]]\u2032s  national championship game.<ref name=ap20150207/> Villanova pulled out to an early 17-point lead and led by as many as 24 points on 12-for-24 three-point shooting, a 50 percent performance well above the 36 percent they had shot from beyond the arc entering the game.<ref name=ap20150207/> In contrast, Georgetown's two leading scorers \u2013 D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera with 15.8 and Joshua Smith with 11.9 points per game \u2013 managed only a combined nine points on 4-for-11 (36.4 percent) shooting,<ref name=ap20150207/> and the Hoyas as a team shot only 1-for-17 (5.9 percent) from three-point range and 30 percent from the field overall.<ref name=ap20150207/> The Hoyas trailed 37-24 at the half and never mounted a comeback, ultimately losing 69\u201353,<ref name=ap20150207/> tying their lowest point total of the season with the 53 points they scored in each of the Xavier games. L. J. Peak with 15 points and Aaron Bowen with 10 off the bench were the only Hoyas to score in double figures.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588449 Georgetown vs. Villanova \u2013 Box Score \u2013 February 7, 2015 \u2013 ESPN Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref>\n\nLosers of three out of four, the Hoyas fell back out of the Top 25, but they promptly embarked on a three-game winning streak with victories at Seton Hall and at home against [[2014\u201315 St. John's Red Storm men's basketball team|St. John's]] and DePaul to improve to 18\u20138 on the season and 10\u20135 in the conference. At Seton Hall, the Hoyas jumped out to a 27\u20137 lead before the Pirates came back to tie the game at 44\u201344, but Georgetown then built a lead again to win 86\u201367; D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera scored a game-high 23 points and Isaac Copeland had two career highs with 20 points and eight rebounds, while Jabril Trawick added 12 points.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588451 Anonymous, \"Copeland, Smith-Rivera help Georgetown beat Seton Hall 86-67,\" Associated Press, February 10, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> Hosting St. John's a week later, Copeland had a double-double with 12 points and a new career high of 10 rebounds, while Smith-Rivera, Joshua Smith, and L. J. Peak also each scored 12, Trawick added 11, and Mikael Hopkins came off the bench also to score 12.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588461 Anonymous, \"Balanced Georgetown defeats St. John's 79-57,\" Associated Press, February 17, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> The win over DePaul four days later \u2013 the Hoyas\u2032 16th victory over the Blue Demons in the past 17 meetings \u2013 gave Georgetown sole possession of second place in the Big East, with Smith-Rivera leading all scorers in the game with 19 points, Joshua Smith recording another double-double (15 points and 10 rebounds), Copeland scoring 12, and Trawick adding 10.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588466 Anonymous, \"Georgetown fends off DePaul from the line, 68-63,\" Associated Press, February 21, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> Traveling to Madison Square Garden for a rematch with St. John's on the last day of February, however, the Hoyas stumbled, losing to the Red Storm despite Smith-Rivera's 29 points and a double-double (10 points, 12 rebounds) and three steals by Mikael Hopkins.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588471 Anonymous, \"St. John's beats Georgetown 81-70 for 20th win,\" Associated Press, February 28, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref>\n\nGeorgetown next visited No. 21 Butler for their second conference meeting and third meeting overall of the season. The Bulldogs forced 15 turnovers and outrebounded the Hoyas 39\u201320, including 17\u20132 on the offensive end, and outscored Georgetown 15\u20132 in second-chance points,<ref name=ap20150303>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588476 Anonymous, \"Georgetown holds off comeback to knock off Butler,\" Associated Press, March 3, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> but the underdog Hoyas blocked ten shots and held the Bulldogs to 35.3 percent shooting from the field.<ref name=ap20150303/> Butler also failed to take full advantage of free-throw opportunities, going 10-for-22 (45.5 percent) from the line.<ref name=ap20150303/> Butler's top-scoring player, junior guard [[Kellen Dunham]], went scoreless for the first {{frac|26|1|2}} minutes and for the final {{frac|11|1|2}} minutes and finished with only eight points.<ref name=ap20150303/> The Hoyas led 30\u201324 at halftime and 34\u201324 early in the second half,<ref name=ap20150303/> but Butler came back to take a 40\u201339 lead<ref name=ap20150303/> with 11:35 remaining. Georgetown responded with five straight points to take a 44\u201340 lead with 8:56 to play.<ref name=ap20150303/> The Hoyas never trailed again, but had to fend off a Butler bid to tie or take the lead in the final seconds with heroics by D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera.<ref name=ap20150303/> With Georgetown clinging to a 56\u201354 lead, Joshua Smith missed a free throw with 10.2 seconds remaining and Bulldog senior forward Kameron Woods grabbed the rebound, but Smith-Rivera stole the ball from Woods and drew a foul by Butler sophomore forward Andrew Chrabascz.<ref name=ap20150303/><ref name=playbyplay20150303>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/playbyplay?gameId=400588476 Georgetown vs. Butler \u2013 Play-by-Play \u2013 March 3, 2015 \u2013 ESPN Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> Smith-Rivera made both free throws to extend the lead to 58\u201354,<ref name=ap20150303/><ref name=playbyplay20150303/> then stole an inbounds pass by redshirt junior forward Austin Etherington with five seconds left,<ref name=ap20150303/><ref name=playbyplay20150303/> drew a foul by Bulldog redshirt junior forward [[Roosevelt Jones]],<ref name=ap20150303/><ref name=playbyplay20150303/> and made two more free throws with four seconds left to seal a 60\u201354 Georgetown upset win.<ref name=ap20150303/><ref name=playbyplay20150303/> Smith Rivera scored 16 points before a home-town crowd in his native [[Indianapolis]],<ref name=ap20150303/> while Joshua Smith contributed 10 and Tre Campbell added 10 off the bench.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400588476 Georgetown vs. Butler \u2013 Box Score \u2013 March 3, 2015 \u2013 ESPN Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref>\n\nGeorgetown completed the regular season by hosting Seton Hall at the Verizon Center. Sidelined by [[heart arrhythmia]] since early in his [[2011\u201312 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|freshman season]] in 2011, Georgetown senior center Tyler Adams had been relegated to the bench ever since under a medical hardship waiver that allowed him to remain on scholarship without counting against the school's scholarship total as long as he did not play, but he had been a steady presence and ''de facto'' assistant coach on the sidelines.<ref name=kilgore20150306/> In a process begun 16 months earlier, John Thompson III arranged for an NCAA waiver that allowed Adams to make a one-possession appearance against Seton Hall on Senior Day, the last home game before his graduation, something Thompson did not announce to Adams or anyone else on the team until two days before the game.<ref name=kilgore20150306/><ref>[https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2015/03/07/georgetown-tyler-adams-scores-senior-day-video Geary, Molly, \"Watch: Georgetown senior with heart issue dunks on Senior Day,\" si.com, March 7, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> Adams started the game and Seton Hall allowed him to make an uncontested dunk almost immediately, giving Georgetown a 2\u20130 lead, to an ovation by the Verizon Center crowd; it was an emotional moment for both Adams and his teammates.<ref name=ap20150307>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400588481 Anonymous, \"Emotional Georgetown holds off Seton Hall 73-67,\" Associated Press, March 7, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref><ref name=vecente20150307>[https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/gtown-senior-with-heart-condition-starts-game-vs-seton-hall-dunks/ Vecente, Sam, \"G'town senior with heart condition starts game vs. Seton Hall, dunks,\" cbssports.com, March 7, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> Thompson immediately called a timeout and Adams exited the game,<ref name=ap20150307/><ref name=vecente20150307/> but Georgetown played on to defeat the Pirates, sweeping the season series with them. Leading Georgetown scorer D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera sat out the game with a lower body injury<ref name=ap20150307/> \u2013 the only game he missed all season \u2013 but Jabril Trawick scored 19 points and Tre Campbell 13.<ref name=ap20150307/> The Hoyas finished the regular season with a record of 20\u20136 overall and 12-6 in the Big East, tied for second place with Butler.\n\n===Big East Tournament===\n{{main|2015 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament}}\n\nGeorgetown rose into the AP Top 25 again, ranked No. 23 before the [[2015 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|2015 Big East Tournament]] began at Madison Square Garden. Under tie-breaking criteria, the Big East Conference considered Georgetown to have finished in second place in the regular season, and so the Hoyas received the No. 2 seed in the tournament, giving them a bye in the first round. They began play in the quarterfinals, facing No. 10 seed Creighton, which had upset seventh-seeded DePaul in the first round to advance to meet Georgetown. The Hoyas led 31\u201325 at halftime,<ref name=ap20150313>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400768446 Anonymous, \"No. 23 Georgetown advances in Big East with 60-55 win,\" Associated Press, March 13, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> but the Bluejays came back in the second half despite the loss of senior guard Avery Dingman, who went to the locker room after suffering an injury in a collision with eight minutes left to play,<ref name=ap20150313/> and Creighton led 51\u201345 with about six minutes to play.<ref name=ap20150313/> With five minutes left to play, however, D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera took control of the game, scoring 12 of Georgetown's final 14 points with a three-pointer, a three-point play, a driving two-point shot as he fell down, and four free throws, the last of which he sank with 3.2 seconds remaining.<ref name=ap20150313/> The Bluejays, meanwhile, committed three of their 18 turnovers during the game's final 2:15. Georgetown won 60\u201355, completing a three-game sweep of Creighton for the season.<ref name=ap20150313/> Georgetown's front court had an off game \u2013 L. J. Peak scored only three points and Isaac Copeland only two, and both were scoreless in the first half \u2013but D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera finished with 25 points and Joshua Smith with 10. Georgetown had 11 steals, three of them by Jabril Trawick,<ref name=ap20150313/> and although Creighton outrebounded Georgetown 31\u201328,<ref name=ap20150313/> the Hoyas had a big advantage at the free-throw line, going 20-for-26 (76.9 percent) while Creighton went 6-for-8 (75 percent).<ref name=ap20150313/>\n\nGeorgetown advanced to the Big East Tournament semifinals for the first time since [[2013 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|2013]] to face sixth-seeded Xavier, which had upset the tournament's third seed, No. 22 Butler, the previous day to advance. Xavier took a 36\u201326 lead at halftime,<ref name=ap20150314>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400784980 Anonymous, \"Xavier holds off No. 23 Georgetown 65-63 in Big East semis,\" Associated Press, March 14, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> and extended its lead to 20 points with 7:53 left in the game.<ref name=ap20150314/> Georgetown then went on a 15\u20131 scoring run, with Isaac Copeland contributing 11 points in a little over four minutes during the rally,<ref name=ap20150314/> while the Musketeers, who led the Big East in free-throw shooting percentage, went 1-for-7 (14.3 percent) from the line.<ref name=ap20150314/> Xavier freshman forward [[Trevon Bluiett]] finally brought the Georgetown run to an end with a three-pointer that gave the Musketeers a 57\u201348 lead with 3:38 left to play.<ref name=ap20150314/> Georgetown continued to close the gap, however, and with 14.7 seconds remaining, Xavier's lead had diminished to 60\u201359.<ref name=ap20150314/> Then the Musketeers began making free throws again, sinking four in a row and extending their lead to 64\u201361 with 4.6 seconds remaining.<ref name=ap20150314/> With 1.9 seconds left to play, Jabril Trawick came to the free throw line for two shots; he intended to make the first one \u2013 which he did, reducing Xavier's lead to 64-62 \u2013 and then deliberately miss the second one to give his team a chance at a rebound and a tying or winning field goal.<ref name=ap20150314/> But Trawick accidentally made his second shot as well, reducing Xavier's lead to 64\u201363 but giving Xavier possession of the ball.<ref name=ap20150314/> The Hoyas fouled Xavier junior forward [[James Farr (basketball)|James Farr]] immediately; Farr made his first free throw at the other end and missed the second, but Paul White grabbed the rebound too late even for one last desperate heave down the court before time expired.<ref name=ap20150314/> Making five of its last six free throws in the game's final 10.6 seconds,<ref name=ap20150314/> Xavier upset Georgetown 65\u201363, completing a three-game season sweep of the Hoyas and advancing to face Villanova in the tournament championship game the following evening.<ref name=ap20150314/>\n\n===NCAA Tournament===\n{{main|2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament}}\n\nWith a record of 21\u201310 and climbing to No. 22 in the AP Poll, Georgetown received a bid to the [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2015 NCAA Tournament]], its 30th appearance in the tournament,<ref name=ap20150322>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400786206 Anonymous, \"5-seed Utah beats No. 4 Georgetown to return to Sweet 16,\" Associated Press, March 22, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> eighth appearance in the past ten seasons, and first since [[2013 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2013]]. Seeded No. 4 in the South Region, the Hoyas opened play in the Round of 64 (known as the \"Second Round\" that season), by meeting the region's No. 13 seed, [[2014\u201315 Eastern Washington Eagles men's basketball team|Eastern Washington]] of the [[Big Sky Conference]], at the [[Moda Center]] in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]]. The Hoyas had lost four of the last five NCAA Tournament games they had played, all of them to teams seeded 10th or lower; Eastern Washington entered the game averaging 80.8 points per game and had the leading Division I scorer in the United States in redshirt junior guard [[Tyler Harvey (basketball)|Tyler Harvey]], who was averaging 22.9 points per game. During an interview on a national radio show the day before the game, Eastern Washington head coach [[Jim Hayford]] extolled the virtues of his team and  promised that the Eagles, who were making only the second NCAA Tournament appearance in school history and first since [[2004 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2004]], would beat the Hoyas in an upset.<ref>[https://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/03/eastern-washington-coach-guarantees-win-over-georgetown Mandel, Nina, \"Eastern Washington coach guarantees win over Georgetown in NCAA tournament,\" usatoday.com, March 18, 2015 3:27 p.m.]</ref><ref name=ap20150320>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400785352 Anonymous, \"Georgetown avoids another upset, beats E. Washington 84-74,\" Associated Press, March 20, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> Joshua Smith got into early foul trouble and spent long stretches on the bench<ref name=ap20150320/> while the Eagles spread the floor and played a fast game, attempting a barrage of three-pointers;<ref name=ap20150320/> they made six of their first 12 three-point attempts, and they hit three of them in a row to take a 24\u201317 lead midway through the first half,<ref name=ap20150320/> raising fears on the Georgetown team that they were destined to lose in another NCAA Tournament first-round upset at the hands of a double-digit seed.<ref name=davis20151218>[https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2015/12/18/bradley-hayes-georgetown-hoyas-john-thompson-iii Davis, Seth, \"After three years on bench, Hoyas\u2019 Bradley Hayes seizing chance to shine,\" si.com, December 18, 2015. Retrieved July 6, 2018]</ref> But with both Smith and Mikael Hopkins on the bench with foul trouble, Thompson turned to unheralded junior reserve center Bradley Hayes, who had spent three seasons in obscurity on the bench.<ref name=letourneau20150320>[https://www.oregonlive.com/march-madness/index.ssf/2015/03/for_georgetowns_bradley_hayes.html Letourneau, Connor, \"For Georgetown's Bradley Hayes, patience pays off on grand stage,\" oregonlive.com, March 20, 2015. Retrieved July 6, 2018]</ref> Hayes responded to the opportunity with the breakout game of his career, playing the final 10 minutes of the first half;<ref name=letourneau20150320/><ref name=davis20151218/> he scored a career-high eight points, making all three lay-ups and both free throws he attempted, pulled down a career-high six rebounds, and recorded an assist.<ref name=letourneau20150320/><ref name=davis20151218/> He did not play after halftime,<ref name=letourneau20150320/><ref name=davis20151218/> but in no small part thanks to his efforts, as well as to the Hoyas sinking their share of three-pointers, Georgetown pulled out to a 43\u201333 lead at the half.<ref name=ap20150320/><ref name=davis20151218/> Hayes's ten minutes of play turned out to be the turning point of the game.<ref name=davis20151218/> Georgetown opened the second half with a 15\u20132 scoring run that culminated in back-to-back three-pointers by D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera, stretching the Hoyas\u2032 lead to 58\u201335.<ref name=ap20150320/> The Eagles closed to a seven-point deficit in the final seconds,<ref name=ap20150320/> but finally succumbed despite Harvey's game-high 27 points.<ref name=ap20150320/> Georgetown won 84\u201374,<ref name=ap20150320/> its first NCAA Tournament victory since [[2012 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2012]], shooting 11-for-23 (47.8 percent) from three-point range for the game, while Eastern Washington shot 9-for-28 (32.1 percent) in three-pointers.<ref name=ap20150320/> Smith-Rivera had 25 points and Mikael Hopkins scored 10 and had nine rebounds,<ref name=ap20150320/> while Jabril Trawick and Paul White also contributed 10 points each.<ref>[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400785352 Eastern Washington vs. Georgetown \u2013 Box Score \u2013 March 20, 2015 \u2013 ESPN. Retrieved July 4, 2018.]</ref> Eastern Washington exited with an all-time NCAA Tournament record of 0\u20132.\n\nThe Hoyas advanced to the Round of 32 (termed the \"Third Round\" this season) for the first time since 2012 to face the South Region's fifth seed, No. 19 [[2014\u201315 Utah Utes men's basketball team|Utah]], which had defeated 12th-seeded [[2014\u201315 Stephen F. Austin Lumberjacks basketball team|Stephen F. Austin]] to advance to meet Georgetown. The game was a contrast between Georgetown's \"[[Princeton offense]]\" and Utah's [[motion offense]], and the Utes had initial trouble with the Hoyas, who used perimeter shooting to build an 11-point lead early in the first half.<ref name=ap20150322/> However, Utah battled back to tie the game at 32\u201332 at halftime<ref name=ap20150322/> and had a 57\u201353 lead late in the second half.<ref name=ap20150322/> The Hoyas kept the game close, and L. J. Peak scored on a layup to hold Utah's lead to 61\u201357 with 3:06 left.<ref name=ap20150322/> After that, however, Utah scored on a three-pointer and a layup to take a decisive 66-59 lead with 1:40 remaining<ref name=ap20150322/> and the Utes went on to upset the Hoyas 75\u201364, bringing Georgetown's season to a close.<ref name=ap20150322/> Peak led the Hoyas with 18 points, Isaac Copeland had 14, D'Vantes Smith-Rivera contributed 12, and Jabril Trawick \u2013 playing his final game as a Hoya \u2013 scored 10.<ref name=ap20150322/> For the sixth straight time since their Final Four appearance in [[2007 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2007]], the Hoyas exited the NCAA Tournament in its first weekend due to an upset by a lower-seeded opponent. They again dropped out of the Top 25 in the final national rankings for the season.\n\n===Wrap-up===\n\nD'Vauntes Smith-Rivera was the team's leading scorer for the season; he missed one game late in the season due to injury but started the other 32, shooting 42.1 percent from the field overall and 38.7 percent in three-pointers, averaging 16.3 points and 4.2 rebounds per game. Joshua Smith played in all 33 games, starting all but one of them, and averaged 10.8 points and 5.8 rebounds per game, shooting 62.1 percent from the field. Jabril Trawick started all 33 games, shooting 49.2 percent in field-goal attempts and 40.7 percent from three-point range, and he averaged 9.1 points and 3.6 rebounds per game. Playing in all 33 games and starting 32 of them, L. J. Peak averaged 7.9 points per game on 39.4 percent field-goal shooting and had 2.3 rebounds per game. Isaac Copeland, Mikael Hopkins, Tre Campbell, Aaron Bowen, and Paul White also played in every game. Copeland had 11 starts and finished with 6.8 points per game on 45.1 percent shooting from the field and had 3.8 rebounds per game, Hopkins stated 24 times, shot 43.8 percent, and averaged 5.1 points and 5.8 rebounds, and Campbell had one start and finished with 3.8 points per game. Bowen and White came off the bench in every game, Bowen shooting 52.9 percent from the field and finishing with 5.6 points and 2.0 rebounds per game and White averaging 5.0 points on 40.4 percent shooting and grabbing 2.8 rebounds per game. Reggie Cameron played in 23 games, all as a reserve, and averaged 1.2 points on 27.6 percent shooting.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/georgetown/2015.html sports-reference.com 2014\u201315 Georgetown Hoyas Roster and Stats]</ref>\n\nJoshua Smith, Jabril Trawick, Mikael Hopkins, Aaron Bowen, and Tyler Adams all graduated after the season. Smith completed his abbreviated Georgetown career of one-and-a-half seasons having played in 46 games, starting all but one, shooting 63.1 percent from the field and averaging 11.0 points and 5.1 rebounds per game; he went undrafted in the [[2015 NBA draft|2015 National Basketball Association draft]] and then played professionally in the [[NBA Development League]] and overseas.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/joshua-smith-1.html sports-reference.com Joshua Smith College Stats Retrieved July 5, 2018]</ref> Trawick had 74 starts in his 126 games, and he shot 46.6 percent from the field for his career, averaging 6.8 points and 2.7 rebounds per game.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/jabril-trawick-1.html sports-reference.com Jabril Trawick College Stats Retrieved July 5, 2018]</ref> Over his five seasons at Georgetown \u2013 his seven-game freshman season cut short by surgery \u2013 Bowen played in 111 games and made one start, and he finished with a 48.3 percent field-goal percentage and 4.1 points and 2.0 rebounds per game.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/aaron-bowen-1.html Aaron Bowen College Stats Retrieved July 5, 2018]</ref> Hopkins had played in 128 games in his four years at Georgetown, starting 75 of them, shooting 42.3 percent from the field and averaging 4.9 points and 3.8 rebounds per game.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/mikael-hopkins-1.html sports-reference.com Mikael Hopkins College Stats Retrieved July 5, 2018]</ref> Adams, sidelined for virtually his entire college career by his heart ailment, had made his real contribution through his support to the team during his four seasons on the bench. He graduated with only 24 minutes played in only five collegiate appearances, four of them early in his freshman season and one \u2013 his only start \u2013 on Senior Day of his senior year.<ref name=tyleradamscareer>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/tyler-adams-1.html sports-reference.com Tyler Adams College Stats Retrieved July 5, 2018]</ref>  He finished his college career with a total of 12 points \u2013 scored on 5-for-10 shooting from the field (one of his field goals being his uncontested senior-year dunk on Senior Day in 2015) and 2-for-2 free-throw shooting \u2013 and nine rebounds.<ref name=tyleradamscareer/>\n\nGeorgetown announced on March 31, 2015, that D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera had decided to forego his senior year of college and enter the [[2015 NBA draft|2015 National Basketball Association draft]],<ref>[https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2015/03/31/georgetown-dvauntes-smith-rivera-enters-nba-draft Geary, Molly, \"Georgetown's D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera will enter NBA draft,\" si.com, March 31, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> a sudden move that surprised observers, who had not ranked him highly as a [[National Basketball Association]] prospect.<ref name=Khurshudyan20150407>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/report-hoyas-smith-rivera-returning-to-georgetown/2015/04/07/cdcf940e-dd79-11e4-a500-1c5bb1d8ff6a_story.html Khurshudyan, Isabelle, \"Report: Hoyas\u2019 Smith-Rivera returning to Georgetown,\" washingtonpost.com, April 7, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref> His decision to depart left the Hoyas facing a rebuilding year [[2015\u201316 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|the following season]]. He did not hire an agent and, with his final year of college eligibility therefore intact, he decided a week later to withdraw his name from the draft pool and return to Georgetown for his senior year,<ref name=Khurshudyan20150407/> causing expectations for the following year's team to soar. Speaking publicly about his decision for the first time on April 30, 2015, Smith-Rivera explained that he initially had decided to enter the NBA draft out of an abundance of confidence in himself and comfort with his abilities as a player, but that his parents had convinced him that returning to Georgetown and completing his education was a wiser choice for the following season.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/georgetowns-smith-rivera-discusses-return/2015/04/30/2d25a200-ef71-11e4-8666-a1d756d0218e_story.html Wang, gene, \"D'Vauntes Smith-Rivera discusses decision to return to Georgetown instead of NBA,\" washingtonpost.com, April 30, 2015. Retrieved July 4, 2018]</ref>\n\nWith Joshua Smith back at center and playing the entire season, the 2014-15 Hoyas enjoyed success, finishing 22\u201311 overall and in second place in the Big East Conference, achieving a national ranking \u2013 No. 22 in the postseason AP Poll and No. 24 in the postseason [[Coaches Poll]], although they dropped out of the Top 25 in both in the final polls of the season \u2013 and returning to the NCAA Tournament after a one-year absence. However, the Hoyas' frustrations in the tournament continued, as they again exited early; in the eight seasons since the Final Four season of [[2006\u201307 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|2006-07]], Georgetown had made six NCAA Tournament appearances without ever advancing past the first weekend, and had gone 3\u20136 in tournament games, each time losing to a lower-seeded opponent. Despite this disappointment, 2014-15 was significant as the last winning season and the last season to include a postseason tournament appearance during John Thompson III's tenure at Georgetown. Although it was not apparent at the time, the Georgetown men's basketball program was about to slide into mediocrity. Over the next two seasons, Thompson would round out his Georgetown career with two straight losing records and no postseason bids \u2013 a trend that would continue after his departure into the [[2017\u201318 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|first season under his successor]], [[Patrick Ewing]].\n\n==Roster==\nWhen he joined the team this season, freshman forward Trey Mourning, the son of [[Alonzo Mourning]], became only the fourth son of a former player to play for Georgetown, joining Riyan Williams, the son of [[Reggie Williams (basketball, born 1964)|Reggie Williams]], who made the team as a walk-on for the second straight season. Other than Mourning and Williams, only two sons of former players had played at Georgetown: [[Patrick Ewing, Jr.]], the son of [[Patrick Ewing]], who played for Georgetown during the [[2006\u201307 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|2006-2007]] and [[2007\u201308 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|2007-2008]] seasons, and Ed Hargaden, Jr., who played during the [[1957\u201358 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|1957-58]], [[1958\u201359 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|1958-59]], and [[1959\u201360 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|1959-60]] seasons and was the son of Ed Hargaden, Georgetown's first [[All-America]]n and star of the [[1932\u201333 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|1932-33]], [[1933\u201334 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|1933-34]], and [[1934\u201335 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|1934-35]] teams.\n\n{{CBB roster/Header|year=2014|team=Georgetown Hoyas|hdr_bgcolor=#001e4c|subhdr_bgcolor=#9c918b|hdr_txtcolor=white|subhdr_txtcolor=#001e4c|high_school=y}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=L. J.|last=Peak|link=y|num=0|pos=SF|ft=6|in=5|lbs=190|class=Fr|home=[[Gaffney, South Carolina]]|high_school=[[Gaffney High School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Tre|last=Campbell|num=1|pos=G|ft=6|in=2|lbs=170|class=Fr|home=[[Washington, D.C.]]|high_school=[[St. John's College High School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Mikael|last=Hopkins|link=y|num=3|pos=F|ft=6|in=9|lbs=223|class=Sr|home=[[Hyattsville, Maryland]]|high_school=[[DeMatha Catholic High School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=D'Vauntes|last=Smith-Rivera|link=y|num=4|pos=G|ft=6|in=3|lbs=218|class=Jr|home=[[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]]|high_school=[[North Central High School (Indianapolis)|North Central]]/[[Oak Hill Academy (Mouth of Wilson, Virginia)|Oak Hill Academy]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Reggie|last=Cameron|num=5|pos=PF|ft=6|in=7|lbs=225|class=So|rs=|home=[[Hackensack, New Jersey]]|high_school=[[Hudson Catholic Regional High School|Hudson Catholic]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Tyler|last=Adams|num=10|pos=C|ft=6|in=9|lbs=254|class=Sr|rs=|home=[[Brandon, Mississippi]]|high_school=Brandon High School|inj=y}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Isaac|last=Copeland|num=11|pos=F|ft=6|in=9|lbs=210|class=Fr|home=[[Raleigh, North Carolina]]|high_school=[[Brewster Academy]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=David|last=Allen|num=12|pos=G|ft=6|in=2|lbs=185|class=Jr|home=[[Dallas]], [[Texas]]|high_school=[[Highland Park High School (University Park, Texas)|Highland Park High School]]|note=W}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Paul|last=White|num=13|pos=F|ft=6|in=8|lbs=185|class=Fr|home=[[Chicago| Chicago, Illinois]]|high_school=[[Whitney Young Magnet High School|Whitney Young High School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Riyan|last=Williams|num=21|pos=G|ft=6|in=4|lbs=175|class=Jr|home=[[Dunkirk, Maryland]]|high_school=[[Archbishop Carroll High School (Washington, D.C.)|Archbishop Carroll]]|note=W}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Aaron|last=Bowen|num=23|pos=F|ft=6|in=6|lbs=205|class=Sr|home=[[Jacksonville, Florida]]|high_school=[[Samuel W. Wolfson High School]]|rs=y}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Joshua|last=Smith|link=y|dab=basketball|num=24|pos=C|ft=6|in=10|lbs=350|class=Sr|home=[[Kent, Washington]]|high_school=[[Kentwood High School (Washington)|Kentwood High School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Trey|last=Mourning|num=31|pos=F|ft=6|in=9|lbs=217|class=Fr|home=[[Miami]], [[Florida]]|high_school=[[Ransom Everglades School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Bradley|last=Hayes|num=42|pos=C|ft=7|in=0|lbs=251|class=Jr|home=[[Jacksonville, Florida]]|high_school=[[Sandalwood High School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Jabril|last=Trawick|num=55|pos=G|ft=6|in=5|lbs=210|class=Sr|home=[[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania]]|high_school=[[Abington Friends School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Footer\n|head_coach=[[John Thompson III]]\n|asst_coach=[[Kevin Broadus]]<br />[[Tavaras Hardy]]<br />Kevin Sutton<br />[[Othella Harrington]]\n|roster_url=http://guhoyas.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/gu-m-baskbl-mtt.html\n|accessdate=November 16, 2014\n}}\n\n==Rankings==\n{{main|2014\u201315 NCAA Division I men's basketball rankings}}\n\nSource<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/seasons/2015-polls.html sports-reference.com 2014-15 Polls]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\"\n|+ Ranking movement<br /><small>'''Legend:''' <span style=\"color:#D8FFEB;\">\u2588\u2588</span> Improvement in ranking. <span style=\"color:#FFE6E6;\">\u2588\u2588</span> Decrease in ranking. <span style=\"color:#FFFFE6;\">\u2588\u2588</span> Not ranked the previous week.</small><small> RV=Others receiving votes.</small><!-- | \u0442 | Tied with team above or below also with this symbol -->\n|-\n! Poll !! Pre<br/>Nov 10 !! Wk 2<br/>Nov 17 !! Wk 3<br/>Nov 24 !! Wk 4<br/>Dec 1 !! Wk 5<br/>Dec 8 !! Wk 6<br/>Dec 15 !! Wk 7<br/>Dec 22 !! Wk 8<br/>Dec 29 !! Wk 9<br/>Jan 5 !! Wk 10<br/>Jan 12 !! Wk 11<br/>Jan 19 !! Wk 12<br/>Jan 26 !! Wk 13<br/>Feb 2 !! Wk 14<br/>Feb 9 !! Wk 14<br/>Feb 16 !! Wk 16<br/>Feb 23 !! Wk 17<br/>Mar 2 !! Wk 18<br/>Mar 9 !! Post<br/>Mar 16 !! Final<br/>Apr 6\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! AP\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFFFE6;\" | 25\n| style=\"background:#FFE6E6;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFFFE6;\" | 21\n| style=\"background:#FFE6E6;\" | 24\n| style=\"background:#FFE6E6;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFFFE6;\" | 23\n| style=\"background:#D8FFEB;\" | 22\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | N/A\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Coaches \n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FFF;\" | RV\n| style=\"background:#FF