{"title_page": "Jupiter Apple", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name    = Jupiter Apple\n| image   = J\u00fapiter ma\u00e7\u00e3.jpg\n| caption = Jupiter Apple at a performance in [[Porto Alegre]], 2007\n| birth_name = Fl\u00e1vio Basso\n| alias = J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3<br>Woody Apple\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1968|1|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Porto Alegre]], Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2015|12|21|1968|1|26}}\n| death_place = Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil\n| resting_place = Cemit\u00e9rio Ecum\u00eanico Jo\u00e3o XXIII, Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil\n| years_active = 1984\u20132015\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter, lyricist, guitarist, bassist, percussionist, keyboardist, record producer, film director, actor, screenwriter, ex-television presenter\n| notable_works = ''A Odisseia: Mem\u00f3rias e Devaneios de Jupiter Apple''\n| module = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = [[Experimental rock]], [[rockabilly]], [[blues rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[progressive rock]], [[art rock]], [[folk rock]], [[rock and roll]], [[Electronics in rock music|synthrock]], [[space rock]]\n| label = Ant\u00eddoto, Trama, [[Voiceprint Records]], Marquise 51 Records, [[Elefant Records]], Monstro Discos\n| instrument = Vocals, electric guitar, classical guitar, bass guitar, keyboards, percussion instruments\n| associated_acts = [[TNT (Brazilian band)|TNT]], [[Os Cascavelletes]], Os Pereiras Azuiz, Bibmo\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Fl\u00e1vio Basso''' (January 26, 1968 \u2013 December 21, 2015), better known by his stage name '''J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3''' and by its [[English language|English-language]] variation '''Jupiter Apple''', was a Brazilian singer-songwriter, lyricist, guitarist, bassist, percussionist, keyboardist, record producer, film director, actor, screenwriter and former television presenter. Before beginning a prestigious solo career in 1994 he was already known for being a founding member of bands [[TNT (Brazilian band)|TNT]] and [[Os Cascavelletes]], both pioneers of the [[Rio Grande do Sul]] rock scene in the mid- to late 1980s/early 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zh.clicrbs.com.br/rs/entretenimento/noticia/2015/12/linha-do-tempo-de-flavio-basso-a-jupiter-apple-a-carreira-do-artista-4936328.html|title=Linha do tempo: de Fl\u00e1vio Basso a Jupiter Apple, a carreira do artista|work=[[Zero Hora]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early years, TNT and Os Cascavelletes===\nFl\u00e1vio Basso was born in [[Porto Alegre]], Rio Grande do Sul, on January 26, 1968; his father was a [[physicist]] and his mother a teacher of German descent.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Basso|first1=Fl\u00e1vio|last2=Manzi|first2=Juli|authorlink2=Juli Manzi|date=2016|title=A Odisseia: Mem\u00f3rias e Devaneios de Jupiter Apple|edition=1st|publisher=Azougue Editorial|language=Portuguese|trans-title=The Odyssey: Jupiter Apple's Memoirs and Daydreams|isbn=9788579202032}}</ref> He learned by himself to play the classical guitar when he was 13 years old,<ref>[http://palcoprincipal.com/bandasMain/jupiter_maca/video/y5XBQE2q8V8 Entrevista de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 para a TV Lim\u00e3o]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730030146/http://palcoprincipal.com/bandasMain/jupiter_maca/video/y5XBQE2q8V8 |date=July 30, 2017 }}</ref> and cites [[Paul McCartney]], [[Syd Barrett]], [[John Lennon]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Brian Jones]] as some of his influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/revistabastiao/docs/bastiao_15|title=Revista Basti\u00e3o #15: Exageradamente Poeta|author=Douglas Freitas, Gabriel Hoewell and Wesley Borges|date=December 2012|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> In 1984 he formed the [[rockabilly]] band [[TNT (Brazilian band)|TNT]] alongside his childhood friends M\u00e1rcio Petracco, Felipe Jotz and Charles Master, being later joined by [[Nei Van Soria]]. TNT reached nationwide notoriety after their songs \"Entra Nessa\" and \"Estou na M\u00e3o\" were included in the 1985 compilation ''[[Rock Grande do Sul]]'', made to promote rock bands from Rio Grande do Sul (such as [[Engenheiros do Hawaii]], [[Os Replicantes]], [[DeFalla]] and [[Garotos da Rua]]) and released by [[RCA Records]].<ref>[http://newyeah.com.br/rock-grande-do-sul-30-anos/ NewYeah.com ~ Rock Grande do Sul \u2013 30 Anos] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> In 1986, one year before TNT released their first studio album, Van Soria and Basso left the band due to creative divergences with RCA to form their own project, [[Os Cascavelletes]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://monkeybuzz.com.br/artigos/11562/cade---tnt---tnt-1987/|title=Cad\u00ea \u2013 TNT \u2013 TNT (1987)|author=Carlos Eduardo Lima|date=September 28, 2014|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> which, despite its relatively short lifespan, managed to release one [[Extended play|EP]], one studio album and a demo. They self-described their irreverent style, characterized by comical and heavily sexually explicit lyrics, as \"[[Pornography|porno]] rock\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/revistabastiao/docs/bastiao_01|title=Revista Basti\u00e3o #1: Com Quantos Paus se Faz Rock 'n' Roll|author=Douglas Freitas, Gabriel Hoewell and Gilberto Sena|date=August 2011|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> The band's most famous composition was the 1989 hit \"N\u00eaga Bombom\", featured in the soundtrack of the ''[[telenovela]]'' ''[[Top Model (telenovela)|Top Model]]''.\n\nOs Cascavelletes broke up in 1992. In 1993 Basso re-joined TNT to record the single \"Voc\u00ea Me Deixa Insano/T\u00e1 na Lona\", but definitely left them again the following year after a falling-out with Charles Master.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/biografias/038341-tnt2.html|title=TNT (Brasil)|author=Daniel Peccini|date=April 6, 2006|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n===Solo career===\nAfter his second departure from TNT, Basso began to perform solo, under the moniker \"Woody Apple\" (as an homage to musician [[Woody Guthrie]] and record label [[Apple Records]], founded by [[The Beatles]]). It wasn't until 1995 when he adopted the stage name he became famous for, J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 (with \"J\u00fapiter\" being an allusion to the fictional spaceship ''[[Lost in Space#Technology and equipment|Jupiter 2]]'', from one of his favorite TV series growing up, ''[[Lost in Space]]''), and formed the very short-lived project Os Pereiras Azuiz alongside Ubirajara Guimar\u00e3es, Rog\u00e9rio Campos and Luiz Wilfrido; they only released a demo tape, ''Orgasmo Legal'', before disbanding.<ref>[http://demo-tapes-brasil.blogspot.com.br/2011/11/jupiter-maca-os-pereiras-azuiz-1995.html Demo-tapes Brasil: J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 & Os Pereiras Azuiz (1995)] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> In 1997 he signed with independent label Ant\u00eddoto to release his first solo full-length album, ''[[A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia]]'', which counted with guest appearances by his former [[Os Cascavelletes]] bandmates [[Frank Jorge]] and [[Alexandre Barea]], and by [[Graforreia Xilarm\u00f4nica]] guitarist [[Marcelo Birck]]; with a heavily psychedelic and experimental sonority comparable to [[Pink Floyd]]'s 1967 debut ''[[The Piper at the Gates of Dawn]]'', the album was critically acclaimed at the time of its release<ref>[http://discofurado.blogspot.com.br/2015/03/jupiter-maca-setima-efervescencia.html Disco Furado: J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 \"A s\u00e9tima efervesc\u00eancia\" (Ant\u00eddoto, 1997)] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> and in 2007 was ranked 96th at ''[[Rolling Stone]] Brasil''{{'}}s [[List of Rolling Stone Brasil 100 Greatest Brazilian Music Records|list of 100 Greatest Brazilian Music Records]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rollingstone.uol.com.br/listas/os-100-maiores-discos-da-musica-brasileira/bi-setima-efervescenciai-jupiter-maca-1996-antidotob/|title=Listas \u2013 Os 100 Maiores Discos da M\u00fasica Brasileira \u2013 '''''A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia'' \u2013 J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 (1996, Ant\u00eddoto)''' \u2013 Rolling Stone Brasil|access-date=May 23, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> Its follow-up from 1999, ''[[Plastic Soda]]'', came out through Trama, and unlike its predecessor, it was fully sung in English; to reflect this, Basso signed the album as Jupiter Apple. It was characterized by an increase in the experimental elements already present in ''A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia'', mixing [[psychedelic rock]] with ''[[bossa nova]]'' and [[jazz]]. Even though it also had a good reception, critics considered it a very hard album to listen to.<ref>[http://discofurado.blogspot.com.br/2015/04/jupiter-apple-plastic-soda-trama-1999.html Disco Furado: Jupiter Apple \"Plastic Soda\" (Trama, 1999)] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> After the album's release Basso temporarily moved to England, returning to Brazil in 2002.\n\n''[[Hisscivilization]]'', his third album, was released soon afterwards by [[Voiceprint Records]], and was his most ambitious and elaborate work;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onotorioabacaxi.blogspot.com.br/2014/08/jupiter-apple-hisscivilization-2002.html|title=O Not\u00f3rio Abacaxi: Jupiter Apple \u2013 Hisscivilization (2002)|author=Matheus Donay|date=August 28, 2014|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> it is composed of 13 mostly instrumental tracks, the longest of which opens the album and is over 11 minutes long.<ref>[http://www.beatrix.pro.br/mofo/jupiter.htm Mofo \u2013 Jupiter Apple \u2013 Hisscivilization] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> Basso experimented more with [[electronic music]] elements in this album, what polarized critics and fans alike.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ocktock.com.br/um-passeio-pela-carreira-de-jupiter-maca/|title=Um passeio pela carreira de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3|author=Leonardo Paiva|date=December 22, 2015|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> In 2003 he moved to Europe once again \u2013 this time to Spain \u2013 alongside his then-[[Domestic partnership|domestic partner]] Bibiana \"Bibmo\" Morena to work on further material; after a 4-year hiatus, both returned to Brazil and he released alongside her the collaborative album ''[[Jupiter Apple and Bibmo Presents: Bitter|Bitter]]'' through Monstro Discos.<ref>[http://gypsyroseproducoes.blogspot.com.br/p/bibiana-morena-os-multicromaticos.html Gypsy Rose Produ\u00e7\u00f5es: Bibiana Morena & Os Multicrom\u00e1ticos] {{in lang|pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://trabalhosujo.com.br/bitter-jupiter-apple-and-bibmo/|title=Bitter \u2013 Jupiter Apple and Bibmo|author=Alexandre Matias|date=July 9, 2007|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Through [[Elefant Records]] and in the same year he released his fourth (and ultimately last) album, ''[[Uma Tarde na Fruteira]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/news_898/062095-jupitermaca.html|title=Disco in\u00e9dito do J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 sai na Espanha|author=Rodrigo de Andrade|date=June 26, 2007|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> It was re-issued in Brazil by Monstro Discos in 2008. \nIn 2009 he released the non-album single \"[[Modern Kid]]\".\n\nIn 2006, six of Basso's songs \u2013 \"Um Lugar do Caralho\", \"Querida Superhist x Mr. Frog\", \"Can\u00e7\u00e3o para Dormir\", \"The Freaking Alice (Hippie Under Groove)\", \"As Mesmas Coisas\" and \"A Marchinha Psic\u00f3tica de Dr. Soup\" \u2013 were included in the soundtrack of the animated film ''[[Wood & Stock: Sexo, Or\u00e9gano e Rock'n'Roll]]'', directed by [[Otto Guerra]]. \n\nOn November 23, 2011, Basso performed live at the Bar Opini\u00e3o in Porto Alegre, accompanied by his newly founded supporting band, J.A.C.K. (an [[acronym]] for \"Jupiter Apple Corporation and Kingdom\"), at the time composed of Julio Sasquatt (drums), Julio Cascaes (electric guitar), Felipe Faraco (bass guitar) and Astronauta Pinguim (keyboards). A DVD of the performance, entitled ''[[Six Colours Frenesi]]'', was released in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/news_814/205613-jupitermaca.html|title=J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 lan\u00e7ando seu primeiro DVD|author=Karen Waleria|date=June 22, 2014|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/news_811/209732-jupiterapple.html|title=Jupiter Apple: Informa\u00e7\u00f5es sobre o DVD \"Six Colours Frenesi\"|author=\u00c1lan Heluany|date=September 4, 2014|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2012, he accidentally fell off the second floor of the building where he lived, and fractured one of his wrists and a [[vertebra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectorsroom.com.br/2012/07/jupiter-maca-cai-de-predio-em-porto.html|title=J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 cai de pr\u00e9dio em Porto Alegre, mas passa bem|work=Collectors' Room|date=July 21, 2012|access-date=August 11, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref> He was then admitted at the Hospital de Pronto Socorro de Porto Alegre, and eventually recovered after a successful surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/musico-jupiter-maca-internado-apos-cair-de-predio-5541250|title=M\u00fasico J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 internado ap\u00f3s cair de pr\u00e9dio|work=[[O Globo]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nHis final releases were the digital singles \"Constantine's Empires\" and \"They're All Beatniks\", which came out through Marquise 51 Records in 2015. The first one is available for listening at the record label's official [[SoundCloud]] page.<ref>[https://soundcloud.com/marquise-51-produtora/jupiter-apple-constantines-empires Jupiter Apple \u2013 CONSTANTINE'S EMPIRES]</ref>\n\nAlongside Tat\u00e1 Aeroplano he wrote and directed the short film ''Apartment Jazz'', which was broadcast for the first time by [[MTV Brasil|MTV]] in 2010.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KBzHoMU_Jf8 Jupiter Apple \u2013 Apartment Jazz]</ref> In 2011 he appeared in \"Kreuko\", a segment of the [[anthology film]] ''[[Mundo Invis\u00edvel]]'', alongside [[Jos\u00e9 Wilker]] and [[S\u00f4nia Braga]]. In 2015 he began work on a second short, ''Jane's Nightmare''; a trailer was uploaded to YouTube on July 15,<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3hXvabgZ9VQ& Trailer of Jane's Nightmare | A movie by Jupiter Apple]</ref> but the film was left unfinished following Basso's death. He also hosted the short-lived talk show ''J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 Show'' on MTV.\n\nBasso played his final show on December 5, 2015 at the Panam\u00e1 Studio Pub, in Porto Alegre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gauchazh.clicrbs.com.br/cultura-e-lazer/noticia/2016/01/colega-de-banda-publica-video-do-ultimo-show-de-jupiter-4961405.html|title=Colega de banda publica v\u00eddeo do \u00faltimo show de J\u00fapiter|work=[[Zero Hora]]|date=January 27, 2016|access-date=February 1, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n===Death and legacy===\nKnown for his extravagant lifestyle, Basso struggled with alcoholism and [[Substance abuse|drug abuse]] (he claimed he took [[Diazepam]] and used [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]] and [[cocaine]] on a regular basis) throughout most of his life, and was undergoing a treatment for [[cirrhosis]] on his later years. On December 21, 2015, he was found dead on the bathroom floor in his apartment;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/rs/rio-grande-do-sul/noticia/2015/12/morre-em-porto-alegre-o-musico-jupiter-maca.html|title=Morre em Porto Alegre o m\u00fasico J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3|work=[[G1 (website)|G1]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> his cause of death was later revealed as being [[Multiple organ dysfunction syndrome|multiple organ failure]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/news_796/235609-jupitermaca.html|title=J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3: divulgada a causa da morte do m\u00fasico ga\u00facho|author=Bruce William|date=December 22, 2015|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> His [[Wake (ceremony)|wake]] was held at the Teatro Renascen\u00e7a in Porto Alegre, and he was buried the following day at the Cemit\u00e9rio Ecum\u00eanico Jo\u00e3o XXIII.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/rs/rio-grande-do-sul/noticia/2015/12/corpo-de-jupiter-maca-e-sepultado-em-cemiterio-de-porto-alegre.html|title=Corpo de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 \u00e9 sepultado em cemit\u00e9rio de Porto Alegre|work=[[G1 (website)|G1]]|date=December 22, 2015|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on his death, Basso's former [[Os Cascavelletes]] bandmate [[Frank Jorge]] said that he was a \"tireless creator, a guy who broke away from all commonplaces and predictability\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/rs/rio-grande-do-sul/jornal-do-almoco/videos/t/porto-alegre/v/fas-e-familiares-se-despedem-de-jupiter-maca-considerado-um-icone-do-rock-gaucho/4691920/|title=F\u00e3s e familiares se despedem de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3, considerado um \u00edcone do rock ga\u00facho|work=[[G1 (website)|G1]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Musician and poet [[Rog\u00e9rio Skylab]] has once stated that Basso was one of his major influences,<ref>[http://tc.batepapo.uol.com.br/convidados/arquivo/musica/ult1753u1594.jhtm Bate-papo com Rog\u00e9rio Skylab | Bate-papo UOL] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> and besides interviewing him for his talk show ''Matador de Passarinho'' he has also covered his songs \"Na Casa de Mam\u00e3e\" (for ''[[Skygirls (album)|Skygirls]]''), \"Eu e Minha Ex\" (for ''[[Trilogia dos Carnavais: 25 Anos de Carreira ou de L\u00e1pide]]'') and \"A Marchinha Psic\u00f3tica de Dr. Soup\" (for ''[[Cr\u00edtica da Faculdade do Cu]]''). Former [[Os Replicantes]] vocalist [[Wander Wildner]] covered \"Um Lugar do Caralho\" for his 1996 solo debut ''[[Baladas Sangrentas]]''. Rock band [[Ira!]] covered \"Miss Lexotan 6mg Garota\" for their 1998 album ''[[Voc\u00ea N\u00e3o Sabe Quem Eu Sou]]''.\n\nBasso's semi-fictional autobiography, ''A Odisseia: Mem\u00f3rias e Devaneios de Jupiter Apple'', co-written by [[Juli Manzi]], was published posthumously by Azougue Editorial in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cultura.estadao.com.br/noticias/literatura,devaneios-de-jupiter-maca-sao-externados-em-livro,10000083678|title=Devaneios de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 s\u00e3o externados em livro|author=Alberto Bombig|work=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]]|date=October 22, 2016|access-date=February 1, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Work on the book began in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/pt_br/article/biografia-jupiter-maca|title=As mem\u00f3rias e devaneios do J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 viraram um livro|work=[[Noisey]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Another biography of the musician, ''J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3: A Efervescente Vida e Obra'', written by journalists Cristiano Bastos and Pedro Brandt, was published on September 5, 2018 by Plus Editora.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectorsroom.com.br/2018/08/vida-de-jupiter-maca-sera-contada-em.html|title=Vida de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 ser\u00e1 contada em livro|work=Collectors' Room|date=August 10, 2018|access-date=August 11, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jornaldocomercio.com/_conteudo/cultura/2018/08/646421-biografia-de-jupiter-maca-e-lancada-nesta-quarta-em-porto-alegre.html#.W45rrncmNeA.facebook|title=Biografia do m\u00fasico J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 conta parte da hist\u00f3ria do rock ga\u00facho|work=Jornal do Com\u00e9rcio|date=September 4, 2018|access-date=September 4, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nOn July 4, 2016, [[Nei Van Soria]] released a song in tribute to Basso, entitled \"Balada para Fl\u00e1vio\". He originally wrote the song in November 2015, one month before Basso's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zh.clicrbs.com.br/rs/entretenimento/noticia/2016/07/nei-van-soria-lanca-musica-em-homenagem-a-jupiter-maca-6378933.html|title=Nei Van Soria lan\u00e7a m\u00fasica em homenagem a J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3|work=[[Zero Hora]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 2017, a documentary about Basso, entitled ''O Garoto de J\u00fapiter'', is being made. Directed by Biah Werther and produced by Gabriel Flag, its production is being [[Crowdfunding|crowdfunded]] through website Catarse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://culturissima.com.br/cinema/documentario-sobre-jupiter-maca-busca-financiamento-coletivo/|title=Document\u00e1rio sobre J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 busca financiamento coletivo|work=Cultur\u00edssima|date=September 16, 2017|access-date=December 22, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catarse.me/ogarotodejupiter|title=O Garoto de J\u00fapiter|work=Catarse|access-date=December 22, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2018, friends of the musician performed a special show in his honor at the Bar Ocidente in Porto Alegre, to celebrate what would have been his 50th birthday on January 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gauchazh.clicrbs.com.br/cultura-e-lazer/musica/noticia/2018/01/amigos-de-flavio-basso-celebram-a-carreira-solo-do-musico-em-tributo-a-jupiter-maca-no-ocidente-cjcz6zetv04wc01kenuedny64.html|title=Amigos de Fl\u00e1vio Basso celebram a carreira solo do m\u00fasico em tributo a J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 no Ocidente|work=[[Zero Hora]]|date=January 28, 2018|access-date=January 30, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 a vinyl deluxe edition of Basso's debut album ''[[A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia]]'' came out through Monstro Discos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rogerlerina.com.br/post/1365/a-setima-efervescencia-ganha-relancamento|title=\"A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia\" ganha relan\u00e7amento|work=RogerLerina.com.br|date=April 2, 2018|access-date=April 6, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Monstro Discos announced in November 2018 that a double-vinyl reissue of ''[[Uma Tarde na Fruteira]]'' was underway; it was released in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tenhomaisdiscosqueamigos.com/2018/11/14/uma-tarde-na-fruteira-jupiter-maca-vinil/|title=''Uma Tarde na Fruteira'', de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3, ser\u00e1 relan\u00e7ado em vinil duplo|work=Tenho Mais Discos que Amigos|date=November 14, 2018|access-date=November 17, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===With TNT===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 1985\n| '''''[[Rock Grande do Sul]]''''' '''(compilation)'''\n* <small>Label: [[RCA Records]]</small>\n* <small>Format: [[Gramophone record|Vinyl]]</small>\n* <small>Contributed with the songs \"Entra Nessa\" and \"Estou na M\u00e3o\"</small>\n|-\n|}\n\n===With Os Cascavelletes===\n: ''For a more comprehensive list, see [[Os Cascavelletes#Discography]]''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 1989\n| '''''[[Rock'a'ula]]'''''\n* <small>Label: [[Odeon Records]]</small>\n* <small>Format: Vinyl</small>\n|}\n\n===With Os Pereiras Azuiz===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 1995\n| '''''Orgasmo Legal''''' '''(demo)'''\n* <small>Label: Self-released</small>\n* <small>Format: [[Compact Cassette|Cassette tape]]</small>\n|}\n\n===Solo===\n====Studio albums====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 1997\n| '''''[[A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia]]'''''\n* <small>Label: Ant\u00eddoto</small>\n* <small>Format: CD, vinyl</small>\n* <small>Re-released in 2018 by Monstro Discos</small>\n|-\n| 1999\n| '''''[[Plastic Soda]]'''''\n* <small>Label: Trama</small>\n* <small>Format: CD</small>\n|-\n| 2002\n| '''''[[Hisscivilization]]'''''\n* <small>Label: [[Voiceprint Records]]</small>\n* <small>Format: CD</small>\n|-\n| 2007\n| '''''[[Uma Tarde na Fruteira]]'''''\n* <small>Label: [[Elefant Records]]</small>\n* <small>Format: CD, vinyl</small>\n* <small>Re-released in 2008 and in 2019 by Monstro Discos</small>\n|}\n\n====Collaborative album====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 2007\n| '''''[[Jupiter Apple and Bibmo Presents: Bitter|Bitter]]'''''\n* <small>Label: Monstro Discos</small>\n* <small>Format: CD</small>\n* <small>Collaborative album with Bibiana \"Bibmo\" Morena</small>\n|}\n\n====Video album====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 2014\n| '''''[[Six Colours Frenesi]]'''''\n* <small>Label: J.A.C.K. Records</small>\n* <small>Format: DVD</small>\n* <small>Recorded in 2011</small>\n|}\n\n====Singles====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Single\n! Album\n|-\n| 2014\n| \"[[Modern Kid]]\" \n| Non-album song\n|-\n| 2015\n| \"Constantine's Empires\"\n| Non-album song\n|-\n| 2015\n| \"They're All Beatniks\"\n| Non-album song\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''Apartment Jazz'' (date unknown; released in 2010)\n* ''[[Mundo Invis\u00edvel]]'' (2011; acted only)\n* ''Jane's Nightmare'' (2015; [[Unfinished creative work#Film|unfinished]])\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''A Odisseia: Mem\u00f3rias e Devaneios de Jupiter Apple'' (Azougue Editorial, 2016; co-written by Juli Manzi)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|jupiterapple}}\n* {{imdb name|4702806}}\n\n{{Os Cascavelletes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jupiter Apple}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Brazilian rock singers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Brazilian rockabilly musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Rio Grande do Sul]]\n[[Category:People from Porto Alegre]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male singers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Brazilian lyricists]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Progressive rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Brazilian classical guitarists]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Brazilian percussionists]]\n[[Category:Brazilian keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Brazilian record producers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Brazilian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Brazilian film directors]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Brazilian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Brazilian experimental musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian singers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian male actors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from multiple organ failure]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name    = Jupiter Apple\n| image   = J\u00fapiter ma\u00e7\u00e3.jpg\n| caption = Jupiter Apple at a performance in [[Porto Alegre]], 2007\n| birth_name = Fl\u00e1vio Basso\n| alias = J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3<br>Woody Apple\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1968|1|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Porto Alegre]], Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2015|12|21|1968|1|26}}\n| death_place = Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil\n| resting_place = Cemit\u00e9rio Ecum\u00eanico Jo\u00e3o XXIII, Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil\n| years_active = 1984\u20132015\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter, lyricist, guitarist, bassist, percussionist, keyboardist, record producer, film director, actor, screenwriter, ex-television presenter\n| notable_works = ''A Odisseia: Mem\u00f3rias e Devaneios de Jupiter Apple''\n| module = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = [[Experimental rock]], [[rockabilly]], [[blues rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[progressive rock]], [[art rock]], [[folk rock]], [[rock and roll]], [[Electronics in rock music|synthrock]], [[space rock]]\n| label = Ant\u00eddoto, Trama, [[Voiceprint Records]], Marquise 51 Records, [[Elefant Records]], Monstro Discos\n| instrument = Vocals, electric guitar, classical guitar, bass guitar, keyboards, percussion instruments\n| associated_acts = [[TNT (Brazilian band)|TNT]], [[Os Cascavelletes]], Os Pereiras Azuiz, Bibmo\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Fl\u00e1vio Basso''' (January 26, 1968 \u2013 December 21, 2015), better known by his stage name '''J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3''' and by its [[English language|English-language]] variation '''Jupiter Apple''', was a Brazilian singer-songwriter, lyricist, guitarist, bassist, percussionist, keyboardist, record producer, film director, actor, screenwriter and former television presenter. Before beginning a prestigious solo career in 1994 he was already known for being a founding member of bands [[TNT (Brazilian band)|TNT]] and [[Os Cascavelletes]], both pioneers of the [[Rio Grande do Sul]] rock scene in the mid- to late 1980s/early 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zh.clicrbs.com.br/rs/entretenimento/noticia/2015/12/linha-do-tempo-de-flavio-basso-a-jupiter-apple-a-carreira-do-artista-4936328.html|title=Linha do tempo: de Fl\u00e1vio Basso a Jupiter Apple, a carreira do artista|work=[[Zero Hora]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early years, TNT and Os Cascavelletes===\nFl\u00e1vio Basso was born in [[Porto Alegre]], Rio Grande do Sul, on January 26, 1968; his father was a [[physicist]] and his mother a teacher of German descent.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Basso|first1=Fl\u00e1vio|last2=Manzi|first2=Juli|authorlink2=Juli Manzi|date=2016|title=A Odisseia: Mem\u00f3rias e Devaneios de Jupiter Apple|edition=1st|publisher=Azougue Editorial|language=Portuguese|trans-title=The Odyssey: Jupiter Apple's Memoirs and Daydreams|isbn=9788579202032}}</ref> He learned by himself to play the classical guitar when he was 13 years old,<ref>[http://palcoprincipal.com/bandasMain/jupiter_maca/video/y5XBQE2q8V8 Entrevista de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 para a TV Lim\u00e3o]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730030146/http://palcoprincipal.com/bandasMain/jupiter_maca/video/y5XBQE2q8V8 |date=July 30, 2017 }}</ref> and cites [[Paul McCartney]], [[Syd Barrett]], [[John Lennon]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Brian Jones]] as some of his influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/revistabastiao/docs/bastiao_15|title=Revista Basti\u00e3o #15: Exageradamente Poeta|author=Douglas Freitas, Gabriel Hoewell and Wesley Borges|date=December 2012|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> In 1984 he formed the [[rockabilly]] band [[TNT (Brazilian band)|TNT]] alongside his childhood friends M\u00e1rcio Petracco, Felipe Jotz and Charles Master, being later joined by [[Nei Van Soria]]. TNT reached nationwide notoriety after their songs \"Entra Nessa\" and \"Estou na M\u00e3o\" were included in the 1985 compilation ''[[Rock Grande do Sul]]'', made to promote rock bands from Rio Grande do Sul (such as [[Engenheiros do Hawaii]], [[Os Replicantes]], [[DeFalla]] and [[Garotos da Rua]]) and released by [[RCA Records]].<ref>[http://newyeah.com.br/rock-grande-do-sul-30-anos/ NewYeah.com ~ Rock Grande do Sul \u2013 30 Anos] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> In 1986, one year before TNT released their first studio album, Van Soria and Basso left the band due to creative divergences with RCA to form their own project, [[Os Cascavelletes]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://monkeybuzz.com.br/artigos/11562/cade---tnt---tnt-1987/|title=Cad\u00ea \u2013 TNT \u2013 TNT (1987)|author=Carlos Eduardo Lima|date=September 28, 2014|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> which, despite its relatively short lifespan, managed to release one [[Extended play|EP]], one studio album and a demo. They self-described their irreverent style, characterized by comical and heavily sexually explicit lyrics, as \"[[Pornography|porno]] rock\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/revistabastiao/docs/bastiao_01|title=Revista Basti\u00e3o #1: Com Quantos Paus se Faz Rock 'n' Roll|author=Douglas Freitas, Gabriel Hoewell and Gilberto Sena|date=August 2011|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> The band's most famous composition was the 1989 hit \"N\u00eaga Bombom\", featured in the soundtrack of the ''[[telenovela]]'' ''[[Top Model (telenovela)|Top Model]]''.\n\nOs Cascavelletes broke up in 1992. In 1993 Basso re-joined TNT to record the single \"Voc\u00ea Me Deixa Insano/T\u00e1 na Lona\", but definitely left them again the following year after a falling-out with Charles Master.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/biografias/038341-tnt2.html|title=TNT (Brasil)|author=Daniel Peccini|date=April 6, 2006|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n===Solo career===\nAfter his second departure from TNT, Basso began to perform solo, under the moniker \"Woody Apple\" (as an homage to musician [[Woody Guthrie]] and record label [[Apple Records]], founded by [[The Beatles]]). It wasn't until 1995 when he adopted the stage name he became famous for, J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 (with \"J\u00fapiter\" being an allusion to the fictional spaceship ''[[Lost in Space#Technology and equipment|Jupiter 2]]'', from one of his favorite TV series growing up, ''[[Lost in Space]]''), and formed the very short-lived project Os Pereiras Azuiz alongside Ubirajara Guimar\u00e3es, Rog\u00e9rio Campos and Luiz Wilfrido; they only released a demo tape, ''Orgasmo Legal'', before disbanding.<ref>[http://demo-tapes-brasil.blogspot.com.br/2011/11/jupiter-maca-os-pereiras-azuiz-1995.html Demo-tapes Brasil: J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 & Os Pereiras Azuiz (1995)] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> In 1997 he signed with independent label Ant\u00eddoto to release his first solo full-length album, ''[[A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia]]'', which counted with guest appearances by his former [[Os Cascavelletes]] bandmates [[Frank Jorge]] and [[Alexandre Barea]], and by [[Graforreia Xilarm\u00f4nica]] guitarist [[Marcelo Birck]]; with a heavily psychedelic and experimental sonority comparable to [[Pink Floyd]]'s 1967 debut ''[[The Piper at the Gates of Dawn]]'', the album was critically acclaimed at the time of its release<ref>[http://discofurado.blogspot.com.br/2015/03/jupiter-maca-setima-efervescencia.html Disco Furado: J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 \"A s\u00e9tima efervesc\u00eancia\" (Ant\u00eddoto, 1997)] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> and in 2007 was ranked 96th at ''[[Rolling Stone]] Brasil''{{'}}s [[List of Rolling Stone Brasil 100 Greatest Brazilian Music Records|list of 100 Greatest Brazilian Music Records]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rollingstone.uol.com.br/listas/os-100-maiores-discos-da-musica-brasileira/bi-setima-efervescenciai-jupiter-maca-1996-antidotob/|title=Listas \u2013 Os 100 Maiores Discos da M\u00fasica Brasileira \u2013 '''''A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia'' \u2013 J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 (1996, Ant\u00eddoto)''' \u2013 Rolling Stone Brasil|access-date=May 23, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> Its follow-up from 1999, ''[[Plastic Soda]]'', came out through Trama, and unlike its predecessor, it was fully sung in English; to reflect this, Basso signed the album as Jupiter Apple. It was characterized by an increase in the experimental elements already present in ''A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia'', mixing [[psychedelic rock]] with ''[[bossa nova]]'' and [[jazz]]. Even though it also had a good reception, critics considered it a very hard album to listen to.<ref>[http://discofurado.blogspot.com.br/2015/04/jupiter-apple-plastic-soda-trama-1999.html Disco Furado: Jupiter Apple \"Plastic Soda\" (Trama, 1999)] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> After the album's release Basso temporarily moved to England, returning to Brazil in 2002.\n\n''[[Hisscivilization]]'', his third album, was released soon afterwards by [[Voiceprint Records]], and was his most ambitious and elaborate work;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onotorioabacaxi.blogspot.com.br/2014/08/jupiter-apple-hisscivilization-2002.html|title=O Not\u00f3rio Abacaxi: Jupiter Apple \u2013 Hisscivilization (2002)|author=Matheus Donay|date=August 28, 2014|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> it is composed of 13 mostly instrumental tracks, the longest of which opens the album and is over 11 minutes long.<ref>[http://www.beatrix.pro.br/mofo/jupiter.htm Mofo \u2013 Jupiter Apple \u2013 Hisscivilization] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> Basso experimented more with [[electronic music]] elements in this album, what polarized critics and fans alike.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ocktock.com.br/um-passeio-pela-carreira-de-jupiter-maca/|title=Um passeio pela carreira de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3|author=Leonardo Paiva|date=December 22, 2015|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> In 2003 he moved to Europe once again \u2013 this time to Spain \u2013 alongside his then-[[Domestic partnership|domestic partner]] Bibiana \"Bibmo\" Morena to work on further material; after a 4-year hiatus, both returned to Brazil and he released alongside her the collaborative album ''[[Jupiter Apple and Bibmo Presents: Bitter|Bitter]]'' through Monstro Discos.<ref>[http://gypsyroseproducoes.blogspot.com.br/p/bibiana-morena-os-multicromaticos.html Gypsy Rose Produ\u00e7\u00f5es: Bibiana Morena & Os Multicrom\u00e1ticos] {{in lang|pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://trabalhosujo.com.br/bitter-jupiter-apple-and-bibmo/|title=Bitter \u2013 Jupiter Apple and Bibmo|author=Alexandre Matias|date=July 9, 2007|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Through [[Elefant Records]] and in the same year he released his fourth (and ultimately last) album, ''[[Uma Tarde na Fruteira]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/news_898/062095-jupitermaca.html|title=Disco in\u00e9dito do J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 sai na Espanha|author=Rodrigo de Andrade|date=June 26, 2007|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> It was re-issued in Brazil by Monstro Discos in 2008. \nIn 2009 he released the non-album single \"[[Modern Kid]]\".\n\nIn 2006, six of Basso's songs \u2013 \"Um Lugar do Caralho\", \"Querida Superhist x Mr. Frog\", \"Can\u00e7\u00e3o para Dormir\", \"The Freaking Alice (Hippie Under Groove)\", \"As Mesmas Coisas\" and \"A Marchinha Psic\u00f3tica de Dr. Soup\" \u2013 were included in the soundtrack of the animated film ''[[Wood & Stock: Sexo, Or\u00e9gano e Rock'n'Roll]]'', directed by [[Otto Guerra]]. \n\nOn November 23, 2011, Basso performed live at the Bar Opini\u00e3o in Porto Alegre, accompanied by his newly founded supporting band, J.A.C.K. (an [[acronym]] for \"Jupiter Apple Corporation and Kingdom\"), at the time composed of Julio Sasquatt (drums), Julio Cascaes (electric guitar), Felipe Faraco (bass guitar) and Astronauta Pinguim (keyboards). A DVD of the performance, entitled ''[[Six Colours Frenesi]]'', was released in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/news_814/205613-jupitermaca.html|title=J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 lan\u00e7ando seu primeiro DVD|author=Karen Waleria|date=June 22, 2014|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/news_811/209732-jupiterapple.html|title=Jupiter Apple: Informa\u00e7\u00f5es sobre o DVD \"Six Colours Frenesi\"|author=\u00c1lan Heluany|date=September 4, 2014|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2012, he accidentally fell off the second floor of the building where he lived, and fractured one of his wrists and a [[vertebra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectorsroom.com.br/2012/07/jupiter-maca-cai-de-predio-em-porto.html|title=J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 cai de pr\u00e9dio em Porto Alegre, mas passa bem|work=Collectors' Room|date=July 21, 2012|access-date=August 11, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref> He was then admitted at the Hospital de Pronto Socorro de Porto Alegre, and eventually recovered after a successful surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/musico-jupiter-maca-internado-apos-cair-de-predio-5541250|title=M\u00fasico J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 internado ap\u00f3s cair de pr\u00e9dio|work=[[O Globo]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nHis final releases were the digital singles \"Constantine's Empires\" and \"They're All Beatniks\", which came out through Marquise 51 Records in 2015. The first one is available for listening at the record label's official [[SoundCloud]] page.<ref>[https://soundcloud.com/marquise-51-produtora/jupiter-apple-constantines-empires Jupiter Apple \u2013 CONSTANTINE'S EMPIRES]</ref>\n\nAlongside Tat\u00e1 Aeroplano he wrote and directed the short film ''Apartment Jazz'', which was broadcast for the first time by [[MTV Brasil|MTV]] in 2010.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KBzHoMU_Jf8 Jupiter Apple \u2013 Apartment Jazz]</ref> In 2011 he appeared in \"Kreuko\", a segment of the [[anthology film]] ''[[Mundo Invis\u00edvel]]'', alongside [[Jos\u00e9 Wilker]] and [[S\u00f4nia Braga]]. In 2015 he began work on a second short, ''Jane's Nightmare''; a trailer was uploaded to YouTube on July 15,<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3hXvabgZ9VQ& Trailer of Jane's Nightmare | A movie by Jupiter Apple]</ref> but the film was left unfinished following Basso's death. He also hosted the short-lived talk show ''J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 Show'' on MTV.\n\nBasso played his final show on December 5, 2015 at the Panam\u00e1 Studio Pub, in Porto Alegre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gauchazh.clicrbs.com.br/cultura-e-lazer/noticia/2016/01/colega-de-banda-publica-video-do-ultimo-show-de-jupiter-4961405.html|title=Colega de banda publica v\u00eddeo do \u00faltimo show de J\u00fapiter|work=[[Zero Hora]]|date=January 27, 2016|access-date=February 1, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n===Death and legacy===\nKnown for his extravagant lifestyle, Basso struggled with alcoholism and [[Substance abuse|drug abuse]] (he claimed he took [[Diazepam]] and used [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]] and [[cocaine]] on a regular basis) throughout most of his life, and was undergoing a treatment for [[cirrhosis]] on his later years. On December 21, 2015, he was found dead on the bathroom floor in his apartment;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/rs/rio-grande-do-sul/noticia/2015/12/morre-em-porto-alegre-o-musico-jupiter-maca.html|title=Morre em Porto Alegre o m\u00fasico J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3|work=[[G1 (website)|G1]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> his cause of death was later revealed as being [[Multiple organ dysfunction syndrome|multiple organ failure]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whiplash.net/materias/news_796/235609-jupitermaca.html|title=J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3: divulgada a causa da morte do m\u00fasico ga\u00facho|author=Bruce William|date=December 22, 2015|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> His [[Wake (ceremony)|wake]] was held at the Teatro Renascen\u00e7a in Porto Alegre, and he was buried the following day at the Cemit\u00e9rio Ecum\u00eanico Jo\u00e3o XXIII.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/rs/rio-grande-do-sul/noticia/2015/12/corpo-de-jupiter-maca-e-sepultado-em-cemiterio-de-porto-alegre.html|title=Corpo de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 \u00e9 sepultado em cemit\u00e9rio de Porto Alegre|work=[[G1 (website)|G1]]|date=December 22, 2015|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on his death, Basso's former [[Os Cascavelletes]] bandmate [[Frank Jorge]] said that he was a \"tireless creator, a guy who broke away from all commonplaces and predictability\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/rs/rio-grande-do-sul/jornal-do-almoco/videos/t/porto-alegre/v/fas-e-familiares-se-despedem-de-jupiter-maca-considerado-um-icone-do-rock-gaucho/4691920/|title=F\u00e3s e familiares se despedem de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3, considerado um \u00edcone do rock ga\u00facho|work=[[G1 (website)|G1]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Musician and poet [[Rog\u00e9rio Skylab]] has once stated that Basso was one of his major influences,<ref>[http://tc.batepapo.uol.com.br/convidados/arquivo/musica/ult1753u1594.jhtm Bate-papo com Rog\u00e9rio Skylab | Bate-papo UOL] {{in lang|pt}}</ref> and besides interviewing him for his talk show ''Matador de Passarinho'' he has also covered his songs \"Na Casa de Mam\u00e3e\" (for ''[[Skygirls (album)|Skygirls]]''), \"Eu e Minha Ex\" (for ''[[Trilogia dos Carnavais: 25 Anos de Carreira ou de L\u00e1pide]]'') and \"A Marchinha Psic\u00f3tica de Dr. Soup\" (for ''[[Cr\u00edtica da Faculdade do Cu]]''). Former [[Os Replicantes]] vocalist [[Wander Wildner]] covered \"Um Lugar do Caralho\" for his 1996 solo debut ''[[Baladas Sangrentas]]''. Rock band [[Ira!]] covered \"Miss Lexotan 6mg Garota\" for their 1998 album ''[[Voc\u00ea N\u00e3o Sabe Quem Eu Sou]]''.\n\nBasso's semi-fictional autobiography, ''A Odisseia: Mem\u00f3rias e Devaneios de Jupiter Apple'', co-written by [[Juli Manzi]], was published posthumously by Azougue Editorial in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cultura.estadao.com.br/noticias/literatura,devaneios-de-jupiter-maca-sao-externados-em-livro,10000083678|title=Devaneios de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 s\u00e3o externados em livro|author=Alberto Bombig|work=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]]|date=October 22, 2016|access-date=February 1, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Work on the book began in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/pt_br/article/biografia-jupiter-maca|title=As mem\u00f3rias e devaneios do J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 viraram um livro|work=[[Noisey]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Another biography of the musician, ''J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3: A Efervescente Vida e Obra'', written by journalists Cristiano Bastos and Pedro Brandt, was published on September 5, 2018 by Plus Editora.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectorsroom.com.br/2018/08/vida-de-jupiter-maca-sera-contada-em.html|title=Vida de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 ser\u00e1 contada em livro|work=Collectors' Room|date=August 10, 2018|access-date=August 11, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jornaldocomercio.com/_conteudo/cultura/2018/08/646421-biografia-de-jupiter-maca-e-lancada-nesta-quarta-em-porto-alegre.html#.W45rrncmNeA.facebook|title=Biografia do m\u00fasico J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 conta parte da hist\u00f3ria do rock ga\u00facho|work=Jornal do Com\u00e9rcio|date=September 4, 2018|access-date=September 4, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nOn July 4, 2016, [[Nei Van Soria]] released a song in tribute to Basso, entitled \"Balada para Fl\u00e1vio\". He originally wrote the song in November 2015, one month before Basso's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zh.clicrbs.com.br/rs/entretenimento/noticia/2016/07/nei-van-soria-lanca-musica-em-homenagem-a-jupiter-maca-6378933.html|title=Nei Van Soria lan\u00e7a m\u00fasica em homenagem a J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3|work=[[Zero Hora]]|access-date=June 10, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 2017, a documentary about Basso, entitled ''O Garoto de J\u00fapiter'', is being made. Directed by Biah Werther and produced by Gabriel Flag, its production is being [[Crowdfunding|crowdfunded]] through website Catarse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://culturissima.com.br/cinema/documentario-sobre-jupiter-maca-busca-financiamento-coletivo/|title=Document\u00e1rio sobre J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 busca financiamento coletivo|work=Cultur\u00edssima|date=September 16, 2017|access-date=December 22, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catarse.me/ogarotodejupiter|title=O Garoto de J\u00fapiter|work=Catarse|access-date=December 22, 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2018, friends of the musician performed a special show in his honor at the Bar Ocidente in Porto Alegre, to celebrate what would have been his 50th birthday on January 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gauchazh.clicrbs.com.br/cultura-e-lazer/musica/noticia/2018/01/amigos-de-flavio-basso-celebram-a-carreira-solo-do-musico-em-tributo-a-jupiter-maca-no-ocidente-cjcz6zetv04wc01kenuedny64.html|title=Amigos de Fl\u00e1vio Basso celebram a carreira solo do m\u00fasico em tributo a J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3 no Ocidente|work=[[Zero Hora]]|date=January 28, 2018|access-date=January 30, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 a vinyl deluxe edition of Basso's debut album ''[[A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia]]'' came out through Monstro Discos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rogerlerina.com.br/post/1365/a-setima-efervescencia-ganha-relancamento|title=\"A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia\" ganha relan\u00e7amento|work=RogerLerina.com.br|date=April 2, 2018|access-date=April 6, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref> Monstro Discos announced in November 2018 that a double-vinyl reissue of ''[[Uma Tarde na Fruteira]]'' was underway; it was released in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tenhomaisdiscosqueamigos.com/2018/11/14/uma-tarde-na-fruteira-jupiter-maca-vinil/|title=''Uma Tarde na Fruteira'', de J\u00fapiter Ma\u00e7\u00e3, ser\u00e1 relan\u00e7ado em vinil duplo|work=Tenho Mais Discos que Amigos|date=November 14, 2018|access-date=November 17, 2018|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===With TNT===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 1985\n| '''''[[Rock Grande do Sul]]''''' '''(compilation)'''\n* <small>Label: [[RCA Records]]</small>\n* <small>Format: [[Gramophone record|Vinyl]]</small>\n* <small>Contributed with the songs \"Entra Nessa\" and \"Estou na M\u00e3o\"</small>\n|-\n|}\n\n===With Os Cascavelletes===\n: ''For a more comprehensive list, see [[Os Cascavelletes#Discography]]''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 1989\n| '''''[[Rock'a'ula]]'''''\n* <small>Label: [[Odeon Records]]</small>\n* <small>Format: Vinyl</small>\n|}\n\n===With Os Pereiras Azuiz===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 1995\n| '''''Orgasmo Legal''''' '''(demo)'''\n* <small>Label: Self-released</small>\n* <small>Format: [[Compact Cassette|Cassette tape]]</small>\n|}\n\n===Solo===\n====Studio albums====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 1997\n| '''''[[A S\u00e9tima Efervesc\u00eancia]]'''''\n* <small>Label: Ant\u00eddoto</small>\n* <small>Format: CD, vinyl</small>\n* <small>Re-released in 2018 by Monstro Discos</small>\n|-\n| 1999\n| '''''[[Plastic Soda]]'''''\n* <small>Label: Trama</small>\n* <small>Format: CD</small>\n|-\n| 2002\n| '''''[[Hisscivilization]]'''''\n* <small>Label: [[Voiceprint Records]]</small>\n* <small>Format: CD</small>\n|-\n| 2007\n| '''''[[Uma Tarde na Fruteira]]'''''\n* <small>Label: [[Elefant Records]]</small>\n* <small>Format: CD, vinyl</small>\n* <small>Re-released in 2008 and in 2019 by Monstro Discos</small>\n|}\n\n====Collaborative album====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 2007\n| '''''[[Jupiter Apple and Bibmo Presents: Bitter|Bitter]]'''''\n* <small>Label: Monstro Discos</small>\n* <small>Format: CD</small>\n* <small>Collaborative album with Bibiana \"Bibmo\" Morena</small>\n|}\n\n====Video album====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n|-\n| 2014\n| '''''[[Six Colours Frenesi]]'''''\n* <small>Label: J.A.C.K. Records</small>\n* <small>Format: DVD</small>\n* <small>Recorded in 2011</small>\n|}\n\n====Singles====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Single\n! Album\n|-\n| 2014\n| \"Modern Kid\" \n| Non-album song\n|-\n| 2015\n| \"Constantine's Empires\"\n| Non-album song\n|-\n| 2015\n| \"They're All Beatniks\"\n| Non-album song\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''Apartment Jazz'' (date unknown; released in 2010)\n* ''[[Mundo Invis\u00edvel]]'' (2011; acted only)\n* ''Jane's Nightmare'' (2015; [[Unfinished creative work#Film|unfinished]])\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''A Odisseia: Mem\u00f3rias e Devaneios de Jupiter Apple'' (Azougue Editorial, 2016; co-written by Juli Manzi)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|jupiterapple}}\n* {{imdb name|4702806}}\n\n{{Os Cascavelletes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jupiter Apple}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Brazilian rock singers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian rock 